animal.description:
Welcome to our beautiful Brindle Warrior, Sloan!
-----
4-6 years old
50-60 lbs
Vaccinated
Neutered
-----
SLOAN the “WARRIOR”?? Or even Sloany Bologna to his friends. 

Sloan is doing great at the rescue ranch. He loves going for walks with the volunteers and loves going into the yards to play. He loves playing tug-of-war and just running around playing chase. He likes to cuddle with his humans and often rubs up against you while he's out playing, just to give/get some love. He has come such a long way from when we got him, he is ready for a home of his own. 
He hasn't spent a lot of time around other dogs. He tends to be dog selective and would need proper introductions when meeting. 

His back story: 
We took Sloan directly to our vet and came to find out that his wounds were not the result of an animal attack or fight but at the hands of humans. The swelling/wound on the side of his head showed signs of blunt force. Meaning he was hit in the head very hard.
The wounds on the back of his neck were more apparent to be gashes like those of a stab wound/punctures from an object, very deep and through one side to the other (the force was so hard that even after healing he will forever have a large knot on his neck where he was attacked).
The chest area has small wounds healing over, possibly from running for a long period through fields or harsh terrain.

animal.description:
Meet Mindy! 
Look who joined Furever Friendz!! Mindy has been in the shelter system since July 2018. She’s been all over.....Hillsborough adopted and returned then back to Hernando adopted and returned. It was determined a few months back that Mindy is deaf. When her time was up.....one of our directors went to say goodbye and he just couldn’t leave her behind even though he himself was going in for surgery the next day. Mindy was always well behaved at the shelter and would not be here with us today if not for our selfless director and him believing in her enough to not leave her behind. Mindy is adjusting well in her foster home. Mindy would do best in a home without other animals as she has so much love to give you wouldn't need another! 

Her adoption fee is $200

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, and current on flea and heartworm prevention.

If interested in adopting Mindy please visit our website www.fureverfriendz.org to fill out an application.

animal.description:
Location: New Orleans, Louisiana 

Annie was  in a local shelter in Louisiana with her litter of puppies. Cane Haven Rescue pulled them from the shelter to give them another chance at life. Annie is approximately 2-3 years old, up to date on vaccinations, spayed & microchipped. 

She would do best in a home with older children or children who can understand boundaries. Annie is best in a only animal home. While she was still living at the shelter, she was an extremely good mother to the puppies. But when the puppies became old enough to leave momma, she was ready too. 

Annie is house trained, kennel trained & knows her basic commands/manners. She is a strong girl but loves attention, sunbathing, and nurturing her babies. 

Interested adopters can fill out an application at canehavenrescue.com. 
Any possible questions about Annie, please email canehavenrescue@gmail.com 

Cane Haven Rescue will transport any of their adoptable dogs to the right home. We do require adoption fees that are based on the age & health status of the adoptable dog. The adoption fee covers every single dog in CHR with vaccinations, heartworm test, deworming, microchip, spay/neuter & medications. All CHR adoptable dogs are current on their monthly  heartworm and flea medication. A CHR representative will do a home check to ensure the pets are placed in a secure and loving home. 

www.canehavenrescue.com

animal.description:
NO APARTMENTS. A HOUSE WITH A SECURE, FENCED YARD ONLY. 

Marlo was abandoned in the middle of nowhere ND in December 2014.  After spending some time at the local shelter and a few months adopted into a home that wasn't a good fit for him, he went into a foster home with Prairie Paws Rescue.  Since he's fostered by one of Journey Home Animal Rescue's founders, he's now available through Journey Home. He loves walks and needs daily exercise.  He loves his people but can be unsure of new people. So a dog savvy owner is a must. He lives with 2 dog savvy cats but would prefer all the attention. He is house trained and kennels up easily.  Marlo would do best in a quiet home without a lot of people coming and going. He is 7-8 years old and weighs about 50lbs. Marlo would appreciate a nice quiet home with a fenced yard where he can be the only pet.

animal.description:
Buddy is a handsome 3-year-old, 75-pound German Shepherd! He’s a fairly laid back guy who loves relaxing at home with his family, playing in the backyard and going for car rides. He enjoys having other large dog friends and does a great job picking up on their energy level and adjusting his own to match. He’s fostered with large dogs and cats and has done well with everyone. Buddy has gone through a 2-week board and train program and is consistent with multiple commands in numerous environments, however, he has shown anxiety toward visitors in his home in the past. For that reason, Buddy needs a confident handler who has large breed experience and will take the time to build a relationship with him and provide clear boundaries so he knows what’s expected of him. He will require a home without children where he will be given several weeks to acclimate before being introduced to new people in and out of the home. Buddy is both crate and potty trained. He’s comfortable in his crate and will need a family who knows when to let him relax in his crate, rather than face visitors or heightened activity in his home. Four private lessons will be provided as part of his adoption fee to help his adopters continue educating and training Buddy and encourage a smooth transition into their family. If you’d like to learn more about Buddy or make him a part of your family, apply today! Buddy's adoption fee is $250.

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

Aylin is a 3 year old female hound/doberman mix.  She has warm heart and wants to be with her people most of the time She is gentle with people and other dogs, but becomes a playtime maniac with her sisters. She LOVES to play and has such a happy spirit! Aylin knows what she wants and lets you know it! She takes treats gently from a hand and never snaps. She likes fresh veggies, especially carrots. And this tall girl is not opposed to helping herself to snacks from the counter or table! Aylin can be shy meeting new people, but warms up quickly. She has not lived with children and has been fine with them with supervision at the dog park, but she really prefers adults and other dogs. She loves to climb into a recliner with her foster parents and take a long snuggly nap and she prefers to be able to lay her head on your shoulder, so be prepared for an occasional lick on your cheek! Aylin has been a complete sweetheart! She will melt your heart when she gazes closely into your eyes. She can run like the wind and would do well with an active family that likes to go for an adventure walk or run.

animal.description:
AGE: 4 years
WEIGHT: 60 pounds
CONDITION: (EPI) Exocrine Pancreatic Insufficiency

Izzy is a good girl with some issues that require a loving family to understand and work with. Izzy has Exocrine Pancreatic Insufficiency (EPI). This means her pancreas does not produce the enzymes needed to properly digest her food. As a result, Izzy requires a special diet. Enzymes and vitamin supplements added to Izzy's food allow her to properly digest her food and gain the important nutrients she needs to be happy and healthy. EPI is thought to be found most often in German Shepherds, but is not restricted to the breed. She must have a family that understands the special needs of EPI and is able to handle a strict diet. 

Izzy came to the rescue as a young puppy and was adopted to a family that eventually sent her to a pound in the Carolinas. She was returned to us with signs of EPI. We began tests and a strict diet, which brought her back to a healthy weight. She is a very smart girl and cannot be left alone outside without a leash or supervised fenced in yard time. She does not do well with cats and cannot go to a home with cats. She is very dog selective and would be best in a one dog family. She is reactive during storms and will react to every storm no matter the size. We do not think she should go to a home with children. She needs an active family that is able to give her purpose and exposure. 

Izzy is currently working with her Advocate Sharon and loves to go for long walks in the nature parks. She does well in the car, but can slip out of most harnesses. She will require a martingale collar or no slip harness when walked with her future family. She needs a firm person to train her and work with her personality. She can escape most enclosures and will need to be in a home that is prepared to work with her on this. This girl deserves a chance and requires a very special person to love and cherish her.

Due to Izzy's EPI and determined personality, we require a full family meet and greet and a two week adoption trial in any home she joins. If you are interested in Fostering or Adopting Izzy, please contact CVRS at info@colbertvetrescue.org.

animal.description: Boaz isnt exactly a new addition to the CHS family. Having been adopted out for the first time in 2017 and recently returned to us, we are now looking for a new forever home for him. Boaz is kind of a complicated kid; he lacks trust in new people when he initially meets them. He is going to be a very loyal companion and an exceptionally good protector. We would not be willing to put him in a home with cats or with kids that are under 16 years of age. This guy is going to need a home where he could stretch his legs and get the daily exercise that he needs. He is very big and very goofy and sometimes has no idea that he is as large as he is. Being a Canaan Mixed breed we would ask that prior to meeting him you please do your research on the breed so that you can understand fully what you are getting into. These guys are known to be protectors of their people, and they will be very vocal, for that reason they are not great at living in the city, there tends to be to much going on and they become overly protective of their property. Boaz also is going to do best in an only dog home. He has a tendency to want to guard objects and stuff from other dogs. He loves a mean game of chase, but we are fairly confident that having another dog in his home would be against what he would actually like to have. He deserves a life of being the most important animal in the home. If you are meeting this kid we ask that you please email animalwelfare@columbiahumane.org and we would be very happy to send you an adoption application. His adoption fee is $250.00 that includes his neuter, microchip, and all of his vaccinations through adoption.For more information call 503-397-4353 or email animalwelfare@columbiahumbia.org

Description:

English Springer Rescue America's mission is threefold: rescue, rehabilitate and rehome. Cyrus is a perfect example of these efforts.

First, he was rescued from poor living conditions with a group of other dogs. The first stop was the veterinarian's, where he was examined, neutered and underwent heartworm treatment.

Second came the rehabilitation. Since Cyrus has basically only known kennel life and was poorly socialized, it is taking some time for him to get comfortable with the things most pet dogs take for granted, like the normal sights and sounds of people cooking, cleaning, talking and laughing. He has learned how to use the doggie door and to go into his kennel for meals and treats.

Now it is time for the rehoming portion of Cyrus' journey. This young man needs a patient Forever Family willing to help him relax and settle in. Because he is still timid, he would do best in an adult home with a fenced yard to explore. He is getting along well with his foster siblings so would probably enjoy the company of another friendly dog.

Hi! My name is Coco Jellybean and I am as sweet as my name implies! I’m 8 years old and in excellent health. The cherry on top? I’m also 100% house-trained. When I’m in the house, I’m very mellow and you can usually find me curled up on the couch – just waiting for you to sit down and snuggle with me. When I’m outside, I love to run and play, fetch the ball, tug on ropes, and romp around the yard. I do enjoy walks and I do well on the leash when it’s just me and my foster Dad. But, when I see another dog headed my way, I have a tendency to pull and I'm very strong! We do continue to work on my leash manners! I'm a smart girl, and am getting better and better. My ideal home would be one with an experienced dog person and one where I can be the four legged queen of the castle - no other dogs or cats or other critters, please. I'm a great excuse to get a great dog but you can't get talked into a second one! Ha! I'm such a wonderful girl, I just don't want to share my space or my toys. I want them all to myself! I just know I would be such a great addition to someone’s family. Could you be the one? ADOPTING TO ILLINOIS ONLY AT THIS TIME

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.
When you "Opt to Adopt" your ADOPTION PACKAGE INCLUDES:
-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neuter/Spay
-Veterinary General Wellness Exam 
-Vaccinations: Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella
-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease  
-De-worming for hook, round, whip and tape worms
-Teeth cleaning if needed 
-New ID Collar, slip leash and ID tags
-Microchip Placement and ID Tag
-Lifetime Registration of your Microchip with Avid microchip company.

There are many wonderful pets who find themselves homeless at no fault of their own.  Thank you considering a rescued companion from all our happy tails and everyone at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation! 
The first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org    
To be considered for the adoption of a pet you must submit the on line adoption application.  We hope to see your application soon.

animal.description:
Update: We heard from a lady that she had lived next to this dog, and his name is Chiquilin....which we have shortened to Chiqui which was his nickname in LA. Unfortunately his owner could no longer care for him, and when he ended up at the shelter he could not afford the medical care that Chiqui by then needed.  He had puncture wounds in his face and was very thin.  We have taken care of the wounds and he is neutered and on the mend.  He is a nice little dog.  Not house trained but we think he can learn  He gets along with everyone and all the dogs. We noticed a seizure some months ago and have not seen another.
More of his back story was that Chi was turned into North central then transferred to low kill  WLA pound with a euthanize date of 11/9 when a volunteer called MCR in a panic due to his sweet personality. We had our puller, Julie, collect him that day and meet up with Anita D who brought him to SLO.  Chiqui does not like crates and will bark if contained. If you have an interest in sweet Chiqui, give us a call at 805-239-4004 or email 4dots@att.net/. Thank you for caring.  UPDATE  Chiqui is now having seizures and a hospice dog

animal.description:
Name: Rosie

Sex: Female

Color: Red & White

Eye Color: Blue Eyes

Birthday: 08/16/2012 (estimated)

Weight: 65 lbs

Large Dog Friendly: Yes

Small Dog Friendly: Rosie has a high prey drive, she should live with dogs 30 pounds and up

Cat Friendly: Due to her prey drive, Rosie cannot live safely with cats

Crate Trained: Yes

Housebroken: Yes

Energy Level: Low

Reaction to New People: Rosie is shy but curious to new people and will sniff and lick them. 

Kid Friendly: Rosie has been around several kids now and has done pretty well. With her skittishness she would do best around kids 7 and older. 

Training: Rosie knows her name, sit, and walks well on a leash (she still gets a little shy about a leash being put on her though). 

Grooming Needs: Rosie has a standard husky coat which will require frequent thorough brushing. You should aim for at least once a week, and more when she is blowing her coat, typically twice a year.

Fence: Rosie is a flight risk due to her past, therefore a fence will be required for her.

Solo or Siblings: Rosie follows the lead of her foster siblings, and will need that guidance in her forever home.

From the Foster: Rosie is a very sweet gal! She came to us when her owner unexpectedly passed away. She lived outside so she learned how to be an indoor dog, but now loves it, especially her favorite spot on the couch. She loves being tucked close to her toys, blankets and in her kennel. She is very timid and is usually on alert. Rosie will need lots of time to adjust to change when she goes to her forever home. With lots of love, training and patience we are sure she will be an amazing dog! Rosie is going to strive best in a home with another dog to help show her the ropes of dog life and a fenced in yard to keep her safe as she is a flight risk. Both are requirements for Rosie.

Adoption Fee: $275

All dogs coming into Adopt a Husky Minnesota receive care tailored to their needs, including:
Nose-to-tail exam with a partner veterinarian, Vaccinations (Rabies, Distemper, Bordetella), 4DX test to check for heartworm or tick exposure, Fecal Analysis, Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative, Spay/Neuter prior to adoption, Microchip, and are evaluated for temperament and trainability.

Professional photos of Rosie were donated courtesy of 27Wolf Photography https://www.27wolfphotography.com/

Stallone is 6 years old and full of personality! He's not for the inexperienced despite his age, but if you are familiar with the breed, he will keep you laughing at his antics. Stallone is great in his crate and sees it as his safe space. He is house trained as well. He would do best in a low key home because when he gets overly excited he can act puppyish jumping around. With his size that can be overwhelming. We are not adopting him into a home with children. He loves to play ball, but doesn't always give the ball up. He's good with other dogs but has only been around larger dogs. Cats are unknown. He is a real challenge to walk on leash as he pulls and is very strong. In addition, he tries to chase cars. He is definitely in need of Obedience training in that area. 
Applications are on our website at www.kodisclub.org

**If you are serious about adopting , you must head to our website and submit a completed application . We will not do anything without an app. Due to the small size of our volunteer-run rescue, only the approved adopter may be contacted. It is not first come first served, but the best match **

Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Meet Aspen! This girl is around  ~6yrs old, and 50 lbs.

 Aspen will be loosing her foster family as of 11/19/20 and will return to her boarding if we cannot find a foster, foster-to-adopt, or adoptive family. 

She isn't the dog for everyone, as she will likely need an experienced dog owner.  Her adopter will need strong dog leadership skills and they must know how to be a good observer and handler.  

Aspen is not an “off the leash at the dog park” kind of dog.  She is “dog selective,” which means she is not going to be friends with all dogs, but she is also not going to try to attack them while on leash, nor bark/lunge at them when she has a dog encounter while walking or hiking.  She ignores other dogs for the most part.  Aspen’s ideal home will likely be one who is looking for just one family dog and has no cats. She does love humans!!  Although she has met children on/off leash and has at times been sweet to them, a home without small children would likely be the best for her.  This ideal home can sometimes include playtime with some dogs she considers friends.  Providing dog training from the start would be perfect .

Medically, Aspen is super healthy!  Even though she may be 6 years old and is happy/content with being calm, she can also be pretty active/energetic and would make a great hiking buddy and enjoys long walks.  Her blood work is great and she recently had a dental treatment, including removing her canine teeth and several other teeth that were fractured from the time before she was rescued.

When she first arrived to the foster's home Aspen seemed to be a little nervous and would whine by the door or in her crate or pant a lot, but with a little love and affection she quickly adjusted and learned the rules fast. She responds very well to “no” and knows which areas she’s not allowed in. She did well with formal training and learned how to not pull on the leash and walk nicely by your side, but you will need to be consistent with it. She only sits when she is on leash by your side with a gentle reminder by pulling up on the leash. 

She enjoys eating leaves from the garden and human food (cooked veggies, rice, sweet potato) over dog food, Probably because they’re soft and easier to chew. She eats hard dog food very slowly because she is missing several teeth, so maybe soft treats and soft food would be better for her.

 Aspen sleeps nicely in her crate every night and will go to her crate on her own throughout the day, however she will resist if she knows you are leaving. Sometimes she will run to a corner or under the bed if you tell her to go to her place, but this can easily be fixed with consistent training on leash (when her leash is on, she goes to her place on command). She is not super destructive but has lightly chewed on a few items that were in the yard (boxing glove and yoga mat), but they weren’t destroyed or anything (again, probably has to do with her missing some teeth). She also responds well to “no” if you see her try to grab something or if you correct her for trying to chew on something.

Aspen is very independent and likes to explore outside.  Several times she has also bolted out of the door, but if you chase her and yell after her she immediately stops and rolls over on her back. Despite her being a little mischievous at times, she is the absolute sweetest. Even though she likes all people and gets along great with everyone, she has attached onto her foster and will follow her around everywhere. She likes to sleep under the foster's side of the bed and it has become her spot at night, or when she wants to get away from everyone. 

She is housetrained and goes on the same place in the yard.

She is dominant with other dogs, but lives with a male staffy rescue  and they are best buddies now, even sleeping with each other on occasion.

animal.description:
Rex is a supersweet, lovable Cattle Dog/Blue Heeler Mix breed. He's a year old old and was found as a stray with his 7 other siblings! He loves to play with his brothers and sisters and gets along well with other dogs. 

The $150 adoption fee includes spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies. Rex is heart worm negative OR are currently being treated with the slow kill method approved by our veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention.

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority but not all of our pets require a fenced yard.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and Good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport a puppy under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees at a low $150, but any additional donations are appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meeting for any of fur-babies. Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events. They are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails.
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped.

Available for adoption to experienced dog owners of working/“difficult” dog breeds (I.e German Shepherd Husky, Akita, Heeler, etc) 

Name: Snow White
Breed: Purebred German Shepherd 
Age: 5-6 years old (as of 2019) 
NOT GOOD WITH DOGS
NOT GOOD WITH CATS
NOT GOOD WITH KIDS

Snow White came to our shelter with her friend named Regina after being seriously neglected by their owner. They spent their lives on a chain where they did not receive the proper care, as well as never experiencing what it was like to be a part of a home and treated as a family member. We are hoping to find someone who is familiar with this breed’s nuances and who will truly love Snow White and give her a second chance at a better life.

Snow White is an independent lady who likes the job of patrolling her grounds. As with many German Shepherd females, she is very confident and self assured. She is protective of her family here at the rescue and is very obedient to her handlers. She loves people and really appreciates walks and a good job to work on. She, also like so many of her breed, needs to have a job to keep from going stir crazy.  She is a high power dog that requires experience with working breed dogs and as an owner knows and expects the demands of the breed. Snow is a good girl! She rides well in a car and puts up with being brushed. She is good about having her nails trimmed and ears cleaned out. She is gentle about accepting treats. She is a big fan of treats and loves dinner time very much.

----
Peach County Animal Rescue is a rescue located in Fort Valley, GA. Our adoption fees range from $250-350+. Although our rescue dogs share a common bond with one another, no rescue story is the same (even when similar). Vetting costs vary depending on their health conditions. All of our dogs are fully vetted: up-to-date on annual shots, spayed/neutered and microchipped with a lifetime registration. We look forward to hearing from you!

If you would like to send in an application for this dog, please use the link below! https://peachcountyanimalrescueandrehabilitation.org/apply-now-2/

Like many rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heart worm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events. ** Please read the bio in its entirety before emailing with questions or submitting an application**

As we are an all volunteer rescue with limited time to respond to emails, if you email us with questions that have already been answered in the bio, we won't be able to respond. We are being inundated with emails at the moment. Thank you for your understanding!

~~Hey, Splinter here! I'm often referred to as Master Splinter by my students, the Turtles, and I'm their martial arts and ninjutsu instructor as well as their adopted father, but in my other life I'm an adorable, tiny gentleman that sure would love to call you my Family!

You are most probably wondering why a handsome 12 year old (estimated by our vet) guy like me is looking for a home. Well, here's my story. I came into the shelter after a really rough life, my owner did not have me neutered, my teeth were in horrible shape, my nails were super long, my skin was so itchy from flea bites that I scratched ALL the time, my tail bone was broken and I'd been shot with a BB. Whew! The worst part is I was dehydrated and emaciated 

I was so happy when PawPrints Animal Rescue took me in and found a foster home for me and Boy has my life changed! Currently I live with my foster mom and her four senior dogs and let me tell you, Life is good! I've been neutered, had a dental and my itchy skin is healing nicely and now I'm ready to find a family of my own.
I don't think I'd do well with young children or with high energy dogs because I have a sore back and the little ones and rambunctious dogs may unintentionally knock into me so I'm looking for someone who can be gentle with me. I love to cuddle but my forever family would have to make sure to lift me on and off the couch so I don't make my back sore again but don't worry, I weigh less than 6 pounds so lifting me would be a breeze! I know I'd make a great companion for an older person who's looking for an adorable lap dog!

I do bark initially when my foster mom goes out but I quickly settle down and mostly sleep while she's away. I must admit that even though I'm pretty close to the perfect companion, I am not 100% housebroken when I am left alone. I do know the meaning of the word "out" but it's most probably best not to let me have free roam of the house while you are gone. I really am a good dog and I hope to work on this now that I am neutered and once I settle into a stable, forever home.

Things have been so confusing lately but if you gently correct me for anything you don't want me to do and praise me for when I'm being your best boy, I will become the most perfect dog ever because I love people and just want to make them happy! In fact, because it makes me so happy to please my person I'd really like to find someone who is retired or at least home a fair amount of time to be with me.

Splinter is 12 years old (approximately), neutered, has had a full dental, tested negative for heartworm and is on monthly prevention, is up to date on his vaccines and microchipped.

Adoption fee is $100 (plus tax for KY residents)

His listing will be removed as soon as he has an approved application

If you have specific needs that aren't addressed in the bio (children in the home, small animals, apartment/condo living, etc) please email to ask if the dog is suitable for the environment before submitting an application. Once the application is submitted, please expect someone to email you with questions and/or provide more information about the dog is we are unsure that the dog may be a good fit.

Most importantly, please be honest! We have many people tell us what they think we want to read, not what's truthful. If there are discrepancies, your application will be denied. It's important for us to place dogs in a home that's suitable. You may be a stellar owner but possibly not a good fit for the dog you were first interested in adopting. We're not trying to offend anyone, we're trying to set everyone up for success. We're a best fit rescue and will verify your vet and personal references.

Adoption Process:

Step 1: Complete a "no obligation" application on our website, www.pawprintsnky.com

Step 2: PawPrints will review the application, verifying Vet and personal references as well as landlord requirements/restrictions (if applicable)

Step 3: IF your application is approved, we will call you to schedule a meet and greet for you to meet the pet.

Step 4: If the meet and greet goes well, we will schedule the home visit.

animal.description:
Chewy von Celle is a beautiful 1-2 year-old German Shepherd and weighs approximately 85#.. This big boy with the soft ears and sweet smile is quite the sharp fellow. Medium-energy Chewy enjoys his walks and is quite observant, always keeping an eye on what or who may be ahead. He is apprehensive towards unfamiliar people and surroundings, and will do best with a shepherd-experienced owner who can introduce him to new faces and friends both slowly and cautiously. With patience, he becomes an easygoing, well-behaved boy who can be very sweet with those he knows, eating up any affection you’ll give him. Off leash, Chewy seems to enjoy the company of dogs (but not cats). He really enjoys canine playgroups, roaming around with his pals and soaking in all the playtime he can fit into his busy schedule. He is loving and attentive, and is seeking a home that will make the most of these assets.


Westside dog Biographies, availability and new photos are updated regularly on our website! So, check in and log on often! 

Westside thanks you for looking at our amazing dogs and for choosing to save an animal's life through rescue. 

Don't forget to visit your local animal shelter...the source of many of our dogs.
 

www.sheprescue.org

https://www.facebook.com/WGSRescue

animal.description:
Say hello to this floppy-eared friend!

After being adopted from FFL as a puppy, Sally was returned to us due to no fault of her own. While we don’t know much about her previous home, we do know that she is growing and learning every day, and she’s enjoying every minute of these new, exciting experiences!

Don’t be surprised if you immediately fall in love with Sally’s big, floppy ears as she runs and plays around outside. Sweet and energetic, she has enjoyed meeting new people and making new friends during her walks and playtime. 

Sally is quickly learning all of the puppy basics, working on her manners, and looks forward to her training time so she can impress her prospective humans. She can’t wait to find a loving family that will call her their own and continue teaching her all the fun things the world has to offer!

animal.description:
Meet Shelby. She is 2 year old.  Shelby needs a patient adopter that will give her some time and training just like her sister. Shelby is more timid then her other sisters and brother. She really needs a family who can really be patience with her give her the time she needs to feel comfortable to come out of her shell. She never bites but will often run from you and hide. She is still learning to be a dog with a human family who will love her and treated her as a part of the family. Shelby scare of human touch all because of her pass. It is so sad to see how scare they are when you try to love on them. She would do best with low key dogs.  Sophie needs that special someone willing to work with her, help her gain her confidence and teach her that people can be good and trustworthy. Shelby, her sibling and mom always wondering the street looking for foods until they were rescue by a sweet kind heart elder lady. It break my heart when I gave her a biscuit she hold it not sure what to do with it. She watch my other dogs and seeing them eating it enjoying it, then she start to enjoy her biscuit. But I know their future have chance since the day they come into my rescue. Sophie is now ready for her furever family and being a part of the family as a member not as a piece of property. 
IF YOU ARE INTERESTING IN SHELBY PLEASE CONTACT CELESTINE 832-659-2576.

animal.description:
LADY & LOUIE were adopted the same day, but from different facilities. They were the same age, puppies, and have been together ever since- except for a heartbreaking separation that almost ended in Lady's death. 
Left at a kill-facility in Las Vegas by their former owner, AnimalVILLAGENM no-kill shelter in NM was contacted. Lady was in the process of being euthanized because she was a pitbull, and considered a 'dangerous dog.' 
During the process of euthanizing her, already sedated for death, the facility decided to check for a microchip. There was one, and  AnimalVILLAGENM said, "YES, WE WANT HER BACK, NO QUESTIONS!" 48 hours later, Lady- and Louie- were safely back in NM, at AnimalVILLAGENM. It was a rough road for the girls, but they are loving their lives again, and must be adopted together. We think you will see that in these pictures!

DOB: 4-16-10
TOTAL Adoption fee for both: $195.

Pet introductions are scheduled when adoption applications are approved. 
Submit $25 application fee with your online application now at animalvillagenm.org/adoption-application

To make sure our pets go to wonderful, safe, responsible homes, we introduce our pets to those who have already submitted complete applications, which have been approved. We adopt only to experienced pet guardians with EXCELLENT veterinary histories, based on conversations with your current or past veterinarian(s.). Please do not ask us to make exceptions.

All information ( and applications ) about our adoption process to adopters all over the U.S. is available at AnimalVillageNM.org.

animal.description:
** Pls READ: Rambo is VERY shy! He needs 1) Another young playful dog in the home &   2) Someone who has experience with fearful dogs. 
Pls folks- take the time to read the bios.  Rambo & his siblings are awesome dogs but it will take time before you see the fun side that we see!

Rambo is a 1.5 year-old Shepherd lab rottie mix. He is 49 pounds. He came from a hoarder situation where he was loved but was not socialized with people. He gets along great with dogs of all sizes but prefers for them not be to dominant.  He's all about the fun dog.  He is very shy with people. He is great with his foster mom but he is definitely considered one of our project dogs.  He needs a loving home with someone who can be patient with his shyness. He would do better in a home with No kids who are going to scare him and he MUST have another playful dog in the house to help teach him that people are good...well some of us are. 

Rambo has so much love to give. If you have love and patience And would like a great reward of earning a dog’s trust please fill out an application and we can set up a meet and greet. 
www.MuttsInNeed.org

animal.description:
Name: Percy
Breed: Lab/Great Pyrenese mix?
Age: 6 years

Trail dog here looking for active humans that promise to take me on hikes
and take me swimming! At 100 lbs I need to stretch these tall legs of
mine! I am a loyal boy and although I love my family, I am nervous around
some strangers especially men. I would prefer a quieter home without a ton
of traffic, and a home as opposed to an apartment!

I am planning to attend a high end board and train program, but apparently
I am in need of "an experienced" couch to crash on when I get out before I
can attend. I am great with the kids in my current home but I would
prefer no kids in my next home. I can be picky with my canine friends, so
for the time being I am looking for a dog free home!

I need someone who will work with me on the training I learn so that WE
(me & YOU!!!) can communicate at our fullest potential!! I LOVE learning
and we could have SO much fun on the trails!!

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please fill out an application at survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions.

He appears curious about the other dogs, so he might be good with another dog in your family, if introduced slowly, and he’s such a nice, sweet guy with people. animal.description:
Shady is about 2 years old now.  In August of 2019, he was hit by a car on a reservation in Manitoba and suffered spinal trauma and a fractured pelvis.. luckily after x-rays and an MRI he didn't need surgery, but needed strict crate rest followed by rehab therapy.

Shady was paralyzed and could not walk, but he has made a miraculous recovery and is now walking, running, playing and is house trained!

Shady has fully recovered from his injuries and has been having so much fun on our 7 acre property.  

He has limited range of motion in his hips, so he tends to bunny hop.  This doesn't cause him any pain, it's just the way he moves now. 

The one thing he cannot do is to Go Down a lot of Stairs.  His brain isn't getting the right signals to his hind legs about that, and may never.  But we do make him go down the 4 stairs to the outside.  He can go up the stairs with ease. 

With that being said, Shady's home should not have lots of stairs and he should never have free access to stairs.  

His ideal set up would be a one level detached home or a home with no access to stairs preferably on a fully fenced acreage, with access to indoors too.  He loves hanging out with his humans while watching tv or sitting on the deck.  He's very attached to his people 

Shady loves having lots of space to run and frolick. Shady also LOVES water!  Swimming is good for him but he should never be off leash swimming in case his legs get tired and he starts to sink.

If you're gone long hours, a doggie door to a secure property would be perfectly ideal for the Shade man.

Shady is great with other dogs, but he is a RUDE player and this tends to annoy other dogs.  He does tend to get over excited, and doesn't fully understand the "quit" signals from other dogs, and this needs to be monitored and controlled by his human to prevent altercations.  He would prefer to live with female dogs over make dogs but if the male dogs is calm, not excitable and non reactive then Shady would make friends. 

 He has met some small dogs but gets over excited and his big feet, over excitable and clumsy nature could injure a small dog, so a home without small dogs would be best..  he is not good with cats 

He still has lots to learn as he wasn't taught much before his injury and since then has been confined for recovery. Especially his recall and stay. 

Shady needs a confident leader who will focus on boundaries and routine. He should not live with any children as he is too excitable and can unintentionally knock them over. He should have an adult only home as he needs consistent routine and boundaries. 

He has a high prey drive for small animals including  cats, squirrels, birds and other interesting critters.  

Shady should not live in highly populated and high traffic areas.  He tends to get overstimulated and over excited, making it hard for him to focus on his human.  When he gets over stimulated he tends to try to nip at passers-by when he is on leash so he will need to be muzzled on leash walks.  Finding Shady a lovely acreage setting would be so ideal.   He loves his current foster home on 7 fully fenced acres. 

His adoption fee is $195.  He is neutered, microchipped, tattooed, dewormed, flea treated and vaccinated..

You can go directly to our website and submit the application by copying and pasting the following link into your browser 

http://lowermainlandhumanesociety.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
It’s hard being homeless, for people and for animals. Thomas was spotted during one of the hottest summers on record, sitting on a piece of cardboard to protect his paws from the grueling hot pavement of a Santa Ana alley, with no food or water in sight. A wonderful woman who feeds feral cats in the area saw him day after day trying to survive when she contacted AALOC, asking us to help this small Chihuahua.  

Thomas is about 10 pounds, a feisty dog with a soft center. He’ll bark when he sees a dog or person he doesn’t know, but gets along well with his buddy Chihuahua friend Jesse and the dog walkers at AALOC. His spirit is a bit broken and we wonder how he could have come to living alone on the streets. You’ll definitely have to build trust with Thomas, but once you do we know you’ll have a friend for life. Thomas can also be possessive of food, toys and your attention, so someone who can provide the necessary leadership and guidance for Thomas is important, and a household without children is required. Chihuahuas are very loyal companions but do not consider their small size – they will protect their owners without consideration of the danger. Therefore they must be protected from bigger dogs, as well as cold weather and falls.  

Please submit an application to adopt Thomas on our website at www.aaloc.org. Once your application is reviewed and approved we will contact you to make an appointment to visit us at AALOC to meet Thomas during visiting hours (10am to 3pm daily) and get to know him a bit.

animal.description:
Simba is a gorgeous young German Shepherd mix, who loves to play with the other dogs in his foster home.  He has an endless supply of energy and would make for an excellent running companion. He will need a lot of exercise and socialization on a daily basis. He’s very intelligent and treat-driven, so he’s been fairly easy to train. He knows how to sit on command and comes when called.  We’re still working on his inside manners, such as jumping up on people, and barking at people walking by on the sidewalk.  He’s house-trained and has been free to roam the house while his foster mom is out, with few chewing incidents.

He will need slow introductions to new people, as he is a bit nervous at first, and will need to meet other dogs in the house to determine if they are compatible.  However, once he gets to know you, he becomes quite the cuddle-bug and will flop over for a tummy rub in a heartbeat.  He is not food-aggressive and sits patiently while his foster mom prepares his and his foster brother’s food.

He definitely has the stubbornness of a GSD but has responded well to positive reinforcement.  He will need an experienced owner who has a lot of love and patience, because he’s a sweet, loving dog, and is definitely worth the effort. 
Please complete an adoption application at
http://www.bigredrescue.com.

help rescue the next pet in need.   As a rescue we

qualities necessary for certain pets.

While some of our pets available have been treated for heart worm or tested heart worm negative all of our pets will be current on heart worm preventative.  All heart worm information is available to all applicants as this information is crucial to the well being of the pet. animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: April 9, 2017 Size: 45 lbs Location: Stone Mountain, GA
RESCUING LEO
Leo came into Cobb County Animal Control as a stray. He has an unknown source of front right leg lameness and some back-end weakness that is more pronounced on slick surfaces. He runs, jumps, plays, and uses stairs 100% like a normal dog. An orthopedic surgeon looked at his x-rays and saw no significant abnormalities, however it was determined he may have some possible nerve damage. Animal Control felt that it would be best if he was placed in a home through rescue to ensure he gets the proper home. FTTF was able to give him his freedom ride on 10/1/18.
ABOUT LEO
Leo is full of himself - he is smaller pittie mix that is full of personality. He bonds really quickly with people and wants to please. Leo loves all people and some dogs. Leo lives in foster care with other dogs and he very much prefers older, lower energy dogs for his friends. He would do best in a home without cats. He walks well on a leash and will gladly show you his happy dance when he sees a human with a leash in their hands. He also loves riding in the car, so much so that if you walk past a car, he will stop and try to get in. (this guy is an excellent travel buddy! He even enjoys going out on the boat!). He is mostly housebroken and crate trained, although he is not destructive and can be trusted out of his crate by himself. He loves snuggling at night and if he could, he will stay sleeping with you all night. This boy is super loving with a medium energy level so he loves to play and run. He is quick and bouncy and a lot of fun.
Leo has an old injury to his front, right leg that has left him with some nerve damage. The delicate paw doesn't slow him down at all, but occasionally causes the 'sleep' sensation, causing him to chew on that paw, but medication for anxiety seems to cut down on that behavior. He does better with traction on grass or carpet than on a hard, slick floor. When on good footing, he gets around perfect and nothing slows him down. He would love a yard to run around in too. Leo is ready for his forever family so if you are looking for a smaller, loving, playful boy Leo is your man!
Photo Album of Leo: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2694938927230923
Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Hello! It’s me Cinder. I used to be called Sorpressa but I never really
connected to that name. One day I heard the volunteers saying I was such
a princess, a “Cinderella” and they changed my name, calling me Cinder
for short. Well, I like that a lot better and I’m so smart, I learned my
new name in a day! I have been at Operation Scarlet for over a year now.
I came here after leaving Puerto Rico and spending more than a year at a
shelter in another state. I get good care here but let me tell you, I’m
more than ready for a real home…..something I never really had. While
here at Operation Scarlet I’ve seen lots of dogs come and go, leaving
Operation Scarlet for their forever homes. I don’t know exactly what a
forever home is but from what I hear it sure sounds like heaven to me.
My dream of a perfect forever home? Well, I am pretty much a princess so
I want a home where I can reign as a true princess….no other pets or
children to compete for attention. What else? As a princess, you know I
need my space. A big fenced-in yard with a nice high fence would fit the
bill. Not having a home my entire 2 years of life, I know I have a lot
to learn about living in a home and I know it will take time and
patience for me to learn how to “dog”. It will be so worth it, for me
and for my subjects, I mean my family. If you’d like to meet me, Cinder
(fka Sorpressa) please go to the Operation Scarlet web site,
operationscarlet.com, and fill out an application. Hours are by
appointment only.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Opal and I am a 11-12 year old snowy white husky with bright blue eyes. 

I am a sweet, timid, older girl looking for a place to retire. I am deaf and have extremely limited vision. My foster momma thinks I can see shadows, but I’m very easily startled and so I am not a good fit for a family with young children. I love to go on walks and bunny hop the whole way! Food rocks my world and I start every day with a happy heart ready for my breakfast! I get along well with other pets as long as they respect my space - I get scared easily since I can’t hear or see very well. Right now my foster mom has two other dogs and a cat and I get along well with all of them!

I am a healthy girl and will come with all updated vaccinations, heartworm test, microchip, recent senior bloodwork and 12 months of heartworm and intestinal parasite prevention. I have already been spayed and have had an extensive dental cleaning (I only have a couple little teeth now)! 

I have been waiting very patiently with my foster mom but I am so ready to find a family that will love me in my golden years! If you think we might be a good match, please email me! Can’t wait to meet you! She can go on a home visit with you for 1 week. If interested in adopting Opal, send an email to adoptions.spspca@gmail.com

COLORADO SPRINGS COLORADO : Meet MACY, a sweet Catahoula X Jack Russel (Possibly Jack Russel) Spayed Female, one year old.  Up to date on vaccs, HW tested and neg, on prevention. Microchipped. Somewhat accepting of crate but not actually crate trained. Has overcome car sickness from puppyhood, Short trips day to day driving she does ok but long distance trips she might get car sick still. Hit and miss at the veterinarian’s office. No muzzle needed but she needs time to settle down and get acquainted. Slow approach from strangers usually wins out. Fed twice a day, Country Naturals.  Treat motivated for training. She probably weighs between 45 and 50 pounds. She is leash trained. She still is puppy focused and does some leash pulling. (Admin note: Recommend a Martingale collar for her )  She does know Heel, sit, stay, down, roll over, paw paw. She has learned some manners. Quick learner. Not much of a barker. Pretty quiet. She is protective of her owner which is a good thing. She is friendly with most people after slow intro’s. She cannot be rushed at all. We are pretty sure that she has some vision deficit and also some hearing deficit in her white ear. We have not tested it out but we see the signs of it. It would be minor not major. Basically we want to stress that she is loyal and sweet and a really good puppy with a lot of potential in the right home. No small children but older children probably ok. She has been around teens, introduced to her properly and has done well.  She goes to doggie day care twice a week and does better with big dogs not smaller ones. She plays very Catahoula rough and rather dominant in play. She has never been around cats but with her hunting drive we would say no small critters for her. Housebroken. 

HISTORY:  She was adopted from a Colorado Rescue at the age of 9 weeks. She has been with her current owner ever since. (ADMIN NOTE: The reason she is with JCLDR on the adopt floor is because we are highly experienced at placing Catahoulas in proper homes.) Owner needs to rehome her because small grandchildren often in the home and incompatibility with older male Golden, just too much rough puppy play and the older dog has bad hips. 

GOOD: Owner loves her smartness and is incredibly loyal. She loves with her whole heart. Loves playing ball and games. She loves to learn tricks. Any game she loves to learn and play. 

BAD: Separation anxiety is getting better but it is still there and she is a bit needy and has some signs of it. Reactive with small children and some noises but she is better with noises. (Admin Note: This can be from her hearing and vision deficit. She hears and sees things in a more intense way) She does improve if you keep working with her. (ADMIN NOTE:  Remember that she is just a baby.) She is pack settled with her family and doesn’t need strangers in her life.. she will interact with strangers respectfully if no one pushes on her. 

UGLY: Small children could turn ugly for her.. no bite incidences yet but owner is very careful to put safety first. 

IF INTERESTED PLEASE CONACT JANEEN JACKSON jj4@midrivers.com or 406-323-3519

animal.description:
From broken to beautiful, Opal is a true story of triumph over adversity.

Opal was picked up as a stray in Houston and to say she was in rough condition would be an understatement. This girl was hairless, emaciated, and suffering. Opal had a tiny patch of hair on her upper back/neck area, the only part of her entire body that contained hair. Her skin was raw, and she had open oozing wounds on her head, likely from scratching. She tested positive for both Sarcops and Demodex.

But that's where her story changes for the better! She was placed into a loving foster home in Texas where her skin, body, and soul all started to heal. She was treated for the skin conditions and her fur grew back and we could see her beautiful coat and coloring.

One of the best things Opal had going for her was her great personality through everything! Opal has every reason to hate people, yet she's just the opposite! Opal is not timid and desperately wants someone to give her love to. 

Opal has already been through so much and deserves a second chance at finding her forever home! 

Additional video: https://youtu.be/tG6Jp2hF2gw

*HOMEOWNERSHIP REQUIRED & BSL RESTRICTIONS MAY APPLY!*

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter

More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/sriracha

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies 1 year and under.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.

NOTE: Applications from Chatham Kent only will be accepted and reviewed.

REQUIREMENTS: Secure fenced yard, another small friendly dog around same age in the home. He would enjoy someone who is semi retired as he is used to someone home a fair amount.  Children over 8 yrs old.  No apartments. NO crating.

Jiggy
Mini Pomeranian
8 years old
9 lbs
Medium Hair
Brown fur
Medium energy level

Jiggy is a shy but friendly little fella but he MUST have someone who will have patience with him for the first few days.  He has gone through so many changes in a short time, it’s confusing for any dog.  Once he has had some time to adjust with an adopter who will go slow and be patient with him, he will warm up and loves to love!  He is a kisser and a dancer, will give you as many kisses as you’d like and will dance when he’s telling you what he wants.   He also LOVES being spoken to – he gets so excited and lights right up when someone chats with him.

Jiggy can get so excited! Especially if he knows he is going for a walk or a ride.   Jiggy is great on his leash and loves to be your car companion.   He gets along with other dogs and is good with children. He does not seem to interact with another dog, but he loves to run and he just loves knowing another one is around. He loves to play and loves his toys.  

IMPORTANT NOTE:  Jiggy does not like to be cornered or feel trapped.  He gets very anxious and will air snap.  He will come to you when he wants attention or wants to be picked up.  He is not 100% trained and has been tested to check for health issue, must be ok with occasional pee inside.

This furry little sweetheart is looking for a home with very patient adopters who will take it slow to give him the chance he deserves for his new home.   He is such a delight to have around, once you meet him you won’t be able to resist! 
 
If Jiggy sounds like the right fit for your home, submit your application at www.ckanimalrescue.com

Adoption fee: $350

Jiggy is neutered, is microchipped, up to date with his vaccinations

Dash was recently rescued from a kill shelter and was taken to a foster home.  This is what his foster family says about him! 

 " Just look at this handsome fella!   My 12 year old daughter has named him Dash and he fits right into our busy family.  He still has a lot of puppy energy and is working on his attention span.  He loves kids of all ages but since he is still working on his manners, I feel small babies would not be the best for him.  He gets along with my small dog and totally respects his boundaries.   I have a larger dog the size of him and they love playing.  Dash is kennel trained, follows simple commands, and works hard to please you.  He is working on walking with the leash and he’s also catching on to playing fetch.  He sleeps out of the crate with my daughter at night with no issues and he’s kenneled through the day while we are at school and work.  He tolerates playing dress up and has had a tea party or two with my 6 year old granddaughter.  He loves car rides and going jogging.  If he could have a regular jogging buddy he would be in heaven.  He can jump a chain link fence to go to find someone to play with so needs a tall wooden fence.   Dash is intelligent, fun, loving and obviously very handsome.

You see, my foster home lives in the country and we go for walks through her property. I love running around but I come back to her when she calls for me. I would also love a home without other animals. Every time I see a dog, I get really worked up and have to take anxiety medication to be able to calm down. My foster home is great and has taught me lots of things like ringing a bell to go outside to potty, she taught me to love my crate, and she is also helping me remember that humans don’t usually like me jumping over the back of the couch - I just thought it was faster! I hope I can find my forever home soon and that my forever humans like playing tug and giving me scratches because I love those too!

Hi, my name is Chopper or Chop as my foster Mom calls me!  I was an owner surrender who ended up at the very scary city shelter.  I sat there waiting for my former person to come back to get me, but they never did.  I was pretty skittish when I got to my foster home but now I am settling in nicely.  My foster Mom says I am a real sweetheart!  I think I am a lap dog and will fall asleep with my head in her lap any chance I can get. Because I had a pretty rough start, I would do best in a home without small children or other pets. What can I bring to a new family? Well, I  am crate trained and potty trained and neutered and up to date on all my shots! I have lots of love to give and will greet you always with a wagging tail.  What am I looking for in a new furever home? I would like lots of cuddles and a gentle hand to pet me, a person or people to play and walk with,  and a soft place to lay my head at night. And someone who will do some training with me so I know the boundaries and can fit well into your home!  If you would be interested in meeting me, please fill out a pre adoption application or send an email and my foster Mom will get back to you just as quick as she can!
XOXOXO-Chop

To access the home page for our group, click on Southern Comfort Maltese Rescue which will take you to the map page.  Below the map is our logo and the link to click on to access adoption forms, contact info or to donate. ALL DONATIONS ARE TAX DEDUCTIBLE.


Adoption Fee: $75.00

Samson is a busy little fella that is 15 years old and weighs just 7 pounds.  His family was no longer able to take care of him so SCMR agreed to help.
 
He does bark for attention and is very loving. Samson just wants to be where he can see his person and be close to them. Sadly he has congestive heart failure and is on two heart medications that he will need to take for the rest of his life: Vetmedin and Enalapril.
 
Samson was a breed dog and has the number 184 tattoo in his left ear, likely for the breeder to keep track of his breeding history. He has cataracts and has some central vision loss but still has peripheral vision. Due to neglect, he has no teeth. Tooth decay probably contributed to his heart condition. He is also not neutered and has an undescended testicle. His heart condition makes surgery inadvisable.
 
Samson is being fostered in Chattanooga, TN for the time he has and is being loved and well cared for.  If there is anyone that would like to sponsor his medical care, please send a donation to SCMR. Thank you.


NOTE: SCMR DOES NOT adopt to homes with children under the age of 10 years or homes with Electric Fences

Out-of-state adoptions are possible; however, the approved adoptive home is responsible for making the necessary arrangements to pick up their new little one.

Meet Greta! This amazing girl was surrendered to a shelter in TX when her owners were not able to care for her anymore. She is 11 years old! It's surprising to us how many senior dogs end up in Rescue. These guys still have so much love to give. Despite her age, Greta is pretty active and enjoys going on walks and playing with the other Mastiffs in her foster home. She is good with kids as well. She's just perfect to us, it's hard to imagine she ended up in a shelter. She is a sweet and happy girl.Greta is safe and loved in one of our 'Hopsice Fosters'. These special foster homes take in the old and terminally ill Mastiffs and keep them as part of their family for whatever time the dog has left. Sometimes that's a few months, sometimes a couple of years. If you are interested in fostering, please contact us! info@greatplainsmastiffrescue.orgSave a Mastiff...Adopt, Foster, Volunteer!

animal.description:
Alma lived the first two years of her life in a home.   Her owners said they did not have time for her, so they moved her outside and tied her to a dog house.   That is how she lived for 2 more years, until her owners decided to breed her.  Then, they decided that was too much for them as well!  She was surrendered to the shelter.

Alma never received any training.  She is a happy dog who does not know how to be social with other dogs.  We are suggesting a home with no other pets, as Alma does not know how to behave around them.   

Alma has not had an accident at her foster home since the first couple days she was there.  We are working on leash skills and basic obedience training.

Alma loves to play.  She will chase tennis balls and loves her bones.  Alma takes treats gently.

Alma is up to date on all her shots.   She has been spayed.  She seems very healthy!  She was wormed, and started on monthly heartgard.  She is microchipped.

Alma is smart and responsive to people~!  She wants to say hi to new people,  and see who they are.

If you are interested in Alma, an application must be processed before you meet her.  References must be checked, and a home visit completed.  If you do not have a fenced in yard (5' please), then you need to demonstrate how she will be exercised.    Please be within a couple hours of N NJ.

Adoption fee is $250.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Alma gets extremely excited when she sees other animals, including dogs.  She is fine if they are outside the fence.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.PHILADELPHIA, PA: *Please Share!* Had a bad day? Need an overall life pick-me-up? Matrix is your man! He will make you feel good. And he will make you feel loved. He's just a GOOD dog. Matrix is a friend to every human he meets. So if you're the type who likes to be social (and when COVID is finally past its peak one day), Matrix will be your perfect co-host-with-the-most! Please give this boy his special chance he deserves at The Good Life. PLEASE SHARE!

All Breed Rescue NE Foster Group wrote, "Matrix is a mixed breed senior pup looking for his forever life! He was 'found' but we believe that was probably the original owner. He was said to be 9 years old. He was pulled in October 2019 and has been in foster. He is friendly with people of all ages.

Matrix's likes: HUMANS, The Phillies, snuggling and having a home. Matrix is super loving and affectionate to any person he meets and always greets new people like a true gentleman! He walks well on a leash/harness. Matrix rocks commands and knows 'sit,' 'down', 'lay down,' 'sit down' and 'wait' (this is used for his meals), and 'drop it.' His goofy personality with lots of wiggles is very endearing! He loves to go for walks and is up for adventures, but is also just as content sitting and cuddling on the couch with you. And don't let his size fool you...he likes to give kisses and sit on your lap like a puppy.

Matrix would prefer to be an only pet and cannot be placed with cats. He weighs about 60 pounds and is in good health. He does use apoquel for dermatitis. He had a full senior wellness blood panel done in January. He can be adopted anywhere from Maryland to Maine and transport will be provided. His senior adoption fee is $150."

To adopt Matrix, please email Sarah at sarah@allbreedrescuevt.com with questions or to apply!

animal.description:
Hi!  My name is Domino.  I am an adult dalmatian mix male, perhaps mixed with bull terrier. who so needs a new home.  I was rescued a few years back from the Rancho Cucamonga shelter and have lived since then with various dogs, including my  good friend, DJ, a female cattledog mix, and after her, Tiffi, a pretty dalmatian girl.  Now I'm living with a group of small dogs and am so missing my female buddies.   I am good with female dogs and non-dominant male dogs, big and small but love the girls the best.  I am a strong sturdy boy, consistent with my breed, so i do need someone experienced with large dogs but with a bit of training and a lot of love, I could be the most perfect pup.  I am neutered, vaccinated and microchipped so I am ready to go handsome big pup like me?

If you are interested in meeting me, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., by email at dalrescue@sbcglobal.net   Rescue will send you an adoption questionnaire to complete or you can access the questionnaire on line from our website homepage, www.dalrescuesocal.com.  Once Rescue gets back the completed questionnaire, and if it looks like I might be a good fit for you and your family, arrangements can be quickly made for you and your family to come meet me at the kennel where I live.   I love meeting new folks so please, contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. and ask about me, Domino.  

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing your posts and photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!
