animal.description:
Mellie is a very attractive small hound mix with a white, brown and black coat. Watch her video of Mellie's gay abandon while playing with her doggie friend.
 Mellie can be very anxious at times. In her foster home she enjoys being with us, sleeping on the couch and spending time in the yard. But she is shy of visitors and is sometimes too timid to come back indoors if she feels new people have been in the house. We haven't managed to get her to walk on the leash and would not adopt her to anyone who wants a dog who must. She will require a home with a very secure fenced yard - at least 6 feet, wooden privacy preferred, which touches the ground. She is frightened if she is not in the yard or the house so trips to the park or walks are not for her. She needs to go to someone who will love her as she is even though we do of course hope that she will continue her very gradual confidence building. 
Mellie likes the cats and tries to play with them but resigns herself to the fact they may only want to curl up with her - lazy old things that they are!
 Mellie was found as a stray with her puppies in someone's backyard. She had been seen running around the neighborhood and was thought to be abandoned.
 Read more about Mellie on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-15-152/.

animal.description:
Ketch is black, white, and tan with floppy ears, and white under her chin and down the front of her neck. Although she has no tail, she wags her little stump.
 A smart, strong-willed dog, Ketch needs a job to do. Obedience, agility or nosework training would be best. Alternatively, she can be someones running partner (she is very athletic). She does require plenty of exercise, both physical (walks, running, agility) and mental (obedience and trick training, impulse control training). Ketch is highly motivated by food and loves to play with toys, which makes training easier. She can, however, be very stubborn at times, so training her requires some effort. We are currently working on basic obedience training with her (Ketch is a jumper and a very strong puller) and impulse control. We are looking for an experienced dog owner who enjoys dog training and is not intimidated by a challenge.
Ketch loves people, but her high energy level makes her unsuitable for families with young children. Ketch has been introduced to other dogs, but she is, unfortunately, not good with them. She will only be adopted to experienced dog owners that currently do not have any other dogs (and do not plan to add new dogs to their family in the future). She cannot be trusted with cats or other small animals, either. Ketch is currently undergoing behavior modification training, which will hopefully make her reactivity to other dogs less prominent. However, we will still only adopt her to single-dog homes. 
Ketch is fully crate- and house-trained. She still has a tendency to chew on inappropriate objects, but providing enough exercise and appropriate chewing items is enough to alleviate this problem. Ketch is healthy, full of energy, and waiting for a patient human who is willing to invest time and energy in her training to help her reach her full potential.
 Ketch was found as a stray and spent several months at a local shelter. While at the shelter, the volunteers spent time working with her, teaching her some basic skills, socializing her in playgroups, and even teaching her to navigate a couple of agility obstacles.
 Read more about Ketch on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-18-050/.

Usagi is an adorable stocky little mixmostly white, with large brown patches and some small, dark polka dots. She is short and muscular with adorable chunky paws. Her big bunny ears usually stand straight up, but sometimes her right ear flops over. Usagi has stunningly gorgeous blue and gold eyes, and a mottled pink and brown nose.
 With her foster family, Usagi is an extremely affectionate little hunk of love. A master of snuggles, she will happily either lie on top of her humans, sprawl out next to them, curl up in the curve of their legs, or smoosh in-between them; big spoon, little spoonshe loves it all. One of her most favorite activities is belly rubs. She will flop onto her back, with paws dangling, and extort all the belly rubs she can. She loves her toys and all food.
Usagi loves to chase a ball, and can run faster and jump higher/farther than most, which would make her great for any type of agility games and training. She occasionally gets the most adorable zoomies and will race in circles, grab a toy, and buck like a little bronco. She is sooooo endearing and provides endless entertainment.
Usagi is very smart and eager to please. She has learned Sit, Down, Stay, Up, Roll over, Spin, Lay on your side, Go to your mat, Wait/Hold (for food or when doors open), Leave it, Come, Kennel up (Go to crate), and a few others! Heres one of the tricks she now knows: she can lie down, with treats lined up on her legs and muzzle, and then, when given the Okay cue, she will gobble them up! Usagi generally walks beautifully on a leash. She is a quick study and would likely be happy to learn any trick requested.
These are just some examples of Usagis amazing qualities and lovable personality. She is, however, very fearful of new things including dogs and people. She has made progress, but in her forever home Usagi will need a patient pet parent/family who will continue to work with her slowly while she builds confidence.
Usagi currently lives with a dog and a cat, but as she has not met most other animals well, she will need to be the only animal in her new home. Her very rambunctious playstyle and bullish affection would also likely overwhelm small children. Usagi is getting braver but still needs very slow introductions to new humans. So, she would not do well in a house with lots of visitors or with people who travel a lot.
Usagi completely melts her foster humans with her sweet, affectionate gaze, the press of one of her meaty little paws, or the smooshing of her blocky head against their cheeks. She will bring boundless love, affection, and laughs to her forever home, and needs loving, caring people to help her feel safe.
For more pictures and videos of Usagi (some with the resident and former dogs in her foster home), check out the Instagram handle @dexeducation.
 Usagi came from a local shelter.
 Read more about Usagi on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-18-031/.

animal.description:
Say hello to Confetti!  She is the life of the party, with stunning good looks and a sweet pittie personality to match!!  

Confetti is fully housebroken, and would love to live with a calm and respectful dog - she is especially fond of chihuahuas!!  She absolutely adores people, and has been to several adoption events because she is such a social butterfly!

Confetti has a neurological condition that throws off her balance but it affects no other part of her life.  She eats, sleeps, and potties just like other dogs, but she requires a bit of assistance while doing things that involve standing or walking.  She has a special harness that she walks with when outside, and she eats out of a raised feeder (while her foster mom holds her steady).  She needs a boost to get up on the couch, but if her foster mom isn't moving fast enough, Confetti will hoist herself up there!  
She is full of confidence and determination, a true testament to the amazing pittie spirit.

Confetti has been going to physical therapy once or twice a week, where she receives laser therapy, walks in the water treadmill, and gets massages.  All of these will help to slow the progression of her condition, and we would like her to continue these sessions after her adoption.  She will also require a home that has very minimal stairs, and that is mostly carpeted.  All of these are to ensure her safety and care. 

If you think you or your family would be a perfect forever match for Confetti, head to rescueapittie.org to fill out our adoption application.

animal.description:
MAVERICK
Staffordshire Terrier Mix
(DOB: 10/28/18)

Maverick is a very handsome young adult male Staffordshire Terrier mix. Weighing just 40 lbs, this little guy likes to carry his toys around, but does shred them to pieces.

Maverick loves to play! He plays hard and runs fast. His favorite game is fetch and he can play it for hours. Maverick is great with people and good with kids. He gets along well with other dogs once properly introduced. He also gets along well with cats and even pigs. 

He is not too submissive or too demanding, but has a calm demeanor. So far his only issue is being reactive on a leash with other dogs and we are working on that.

Maverick is up-to-date on vaccines, neutered, microchipped and being maintained on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. He is house-trained and crate-trained. 

Maverick has gone through some basic training. He has learned the SIT and DOWN commands and walks well on a leash – even off leash he walks right beside his foster parents.

Maverick loves to go for car rides and take on new adventures. He recently went to the mountains and enjoyed the snow. He walked through creeks and explored everything.

If you’re looking for a new family member who is active and playful, please consider inviting Maverick into your life.

This dog is currently being fostered as part of Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue. An application is required, along with a home visit and small adoption fee.  Applicants must be at least 21 years of age. **FENCED IN YARD REQUIRED**

Please visit us on our Facebook page for additional photos, give us a like while you're there! 
https://www.facebook.com/diamondsintheruffNC

All of our dogs are fostered in homes and are INDOOR dogs. We believe all dogs are family members and should be treated as valued members of the household. 

Please review our adoption guidelines for further information on adopting from Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue before submitting an application. www.DITRnc.com.


.

Beamer is a permanent puppy with long, gangly legs and ridiculous, puppy-dog eyes. Beamer is such a goofball and is looking for the peanut butter to his jelly.

Beamer is very food/treat motivated and will obey if he knows he is going to get a treat. He knows all the basic commands (sit, down, shake, stay) as well as "High Five". We have taught him to "Find it" which is his favorite indoor game. We make him stay as we walk around with a treat in hand touching numerous surfaces to leave the scent; once we place the treat "hidden" somewhere, we let him smell our hand and then tell him to "Find It". It is really fun watching him go from place to place trying to find the treat.

Beamer enjoys daily walks and being active. He would be a fantastic running partner or hiking companion for any Coloradan. Just like any dog, if Beamer is left unstimulated (mentally or physically), he can become destructive. Weve learned Beamer loves hard chew toys, like antlers, nylabones, and Kongs.

Beamer is fully house-trained and has to wait to poop or pee while on a walk until he gets home. He ALWAYS waits until we get home and has "his spot". He's never had any accidents in the house.

Our beloved Beamer is a graduate of Golden Heart Canine's board and train program, which means he's got mad skills. He is still a giant puppy and clumsy, but at least he's got skills. In board and train, he learned to walk properly on a leash, learn patience (which may have been the hardest part for him), and how to be around other dogs without being uncontrollable. His forever home will need to continue to reinforce these skills.

Beamer is one of our Single Shamrocks. A #SingleShamrock is a dog who needs to be the only dog in the home, so no other pets and children older than 13 years old. If you're interested in FOSTERING or ADOPTING him, please complete an application here: http://2babrescue.org/adoption-application

*BSL Restrictions may apply.

To see video's of Beamer's board & train program, please see below.


	Beamer Video 1 https://photos.app.goo.gl/X2gN3Zkt2smVm2Jc7 
	Beamer Video 2 https://photos.app.goo.gl/3Jk5vYNWjrwmh3uB6


Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

I work on the sites everyday and keep them updated.  Be sure to add us to your contact list on email or we could be trying to email you and it could go to spam.
Courtesy ShyLow (Shiloh) came to us September of 2018 at 7 months old. So we made her birthdate on Valentine’s Day. She loves her humans and loves snuggles. She loves to jump up and give hugs. She likes to lick your hand as you walk with her. She is a free roamer and has not been leash trained. Although the few times she’s used one she does good. She is crate trained (sleep in crate all night) and house trained. For being almost 2 she is very energetic. She has not been around cats, livestock or small children so not sure how she will do with them. She gets along wonderfully with my 12 & 19 year old sons. She loves her dog brothers but is jealous of her dog sisters. She has become aggressive to the other two female dogs in the home. So she must be an only female or only dog. Her brothers are smaller and larger than her and has not had issues with any of the three. •She is a fixed Female Boxer/ Shepherd mix. •She is chipped. •She is vaccinated. •Flea & Tick preventives. •Heart worm preventives. •Eats dry dog food “Pedigree Complete Nutrition Adult Dog Food” Adoption fee $85
We are foster based only (No shelter) you can't just drive up here and get a pet. If you are interested in a animal fill out the form, not a binding contract to adopt. This is how we get your information to the foster, most of our foster live in the Stillwater Ok. Area. Application to meet                                                                                       https://form.jotform.com/200005720739042 

We do adopt out of state but we do not ship animals, If you want to adopt one of our animals, you must come to pick them up in Oklahoma.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bette grew up on a small farm guarding goats, and when her elderly owner could no longer take care of the farm, the goats were sold and Bette was surrendered to us. She is a very sweet girl who is perfectly safe with goats and chickens, but she has decided that she prefers living inside the house. She is house/potty-trained and crate-trained.

Bette gets along well with other dogs of all sizes, and is playful with most dogs. She loves people but isn't annoying about asking for so much attention that she seems needy.

Bette DOES need secure fencing, and if you leave her outside unattended too much, she may get bored and try to dig under or climb over the fence. The best solution (other than 6' or taller fencing) -- just don't leave her in the yard and ignore her. Make her part of your family, whether that's inside the house or when you're enjoying your back yard.

NOTE: You'll see one close-up photo of Bette with stitches on her muzzle. When she was still living in the pasture as a livestock guardian, she showed up one day in a different pasture (still on our property) and she had a cut on her muzzle. We believe she got the cut from digging under the fence, but it's possible she snagged it going over rather than under. Either way, that was our cue to move her from the pasture to the house.

Overall, Bette is a great dog and easy to have around. If she sounds like the perfect companion for you, please read about our adoption process and requirements, and submit your application on our website at www.bluebonnetrescue.org/info/adoption.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name - Will
Nicknames - None
Age - Adult
Weight - 50 lbs
Other dogs - Great with dogs Very playful and loving
Cats - could live with dog savvy cats under supervision as he will chase if given the opportunity. But can co-exist under supervision.
Chickens - No
Kids - kid friendly
Background - Will is one of 5 dogs we flew down from a shelter up north. He came into the shelter as a stray and so not much about his history before the rescue is known
Health issues - He trembles when he is nervous, mostly in his back leg. He gets stiff if he lays down too long - mostly in the colder weather. He takes daily medication to help with the joint stiffness
Crate trained - Is not a fan of the crate and does have separation anxiety. He is best left out with his doggy sibling and only for short periods of time
Leash trained - Mostly yes with room for improvements
Housebroken - Is used to using a doggy door and have the ability to go outside whenever he chooses
Eating Habits - Very Good. Not picky. Does not beg for table food.
Commands known - Sit, Stay, Wait. Very smart when he figures out what you want
Car rides - Good. Not nervous, likes to look out window. Uses harness seat belt
Bath time - Not his favorite activity
Affectionate - Very loving and follows you everywhere. Loves to have his head scratched and belly rubbed
Activity level - Due to the stiffness in joints low to medium. Short walks are good and he likes to zoomie in the backyard. Perfect for a couch potato who wants to cuddle
Play style - Push/pull style with foster sister but ultimately more submissive. Loves chewing on bones and learning how to play fetch. When relaxing, he cuddles and sleeps with foster sister and likes to groom her
Bad habits - Separation anxiety, which is improving. He must be left in a larger contained area (not a crate, think baby gated room) with access to outside for potty. Only bones or appropriate toys left out so he does not chew on anything he's not supposed to. Oh and he dunks his whole face in the water bowl so be prepared for a little slobber

Redeeming qualities - Very loving and just wants to be near you. Eager to please and very trainable. Doesn't bark at other dogs but does like to "talk" to you when he gets excited
Best feature - Has little black eyebrows and a black mustache. One ear that stands up and one that folds over. Has a very soulful face that makes you think that he has been through a lot. He's an old soul. Likes to put his face between the chair cushion and armrest and gets this squishy face and pitiful eyes that just make you want to do anything for him. He's very willing to learn. Only took 3 times of putting his food bowl in front of him and telling him to "wait" and now he does and looks to me for the "ok". Knows the negative "uhh uhh" sound and stops doing whatever he is doing and focuses on you. Example: we have an Alexa Show and one time I was checking on him when I was gone and he had gotten into something and I gave the "no" sound, and though he couldn't see me, just hearing me made him stop what he was doing!

What Foster Mom/Dad wants you to know -
"Will came to us with a very strong will and wanting to do what HE wanted to do, I think this was a survival attitude that he had to have just to survive, being a stray. With lots of patience and work and letting him learn what it means to be a dog, he is finally giving us the authority to take care of him. Is he still stubborn? Yes. Does he still have separation and barrier anxiety? Yes. But, the most important thing about Will is that he is improving so much and we can see that he has a lot to give to the right people. He tries, REALLY tries to do the right thing. He is very smart and learns things quickly. He loves to be your shadow and follow you from room to room and let you know that he does it because he loves you. It's his way of showing it. He is playful and good with our other dog. He snuggles up with her in the same doggy bed and will groom her and just lay down. He has quiet times where he likes to just lay on his bed and he sleeps through the night out of the cage and without people in the room (another thing he has learned!). I love that he doesn't bark when people come over or when the neighbor's dogs come to the fence. He does let me know by becoming alert that he heard something outside or the Ring doorbell went off! Will will win your hearts and soul, and with the time, training, and patience, he is really going to be an extraordinary dog!"

Please consider sponsoring Will with either a one-time or monthly tax-deductible donation. Your donation will help It's The Pits with day-to-day care, including food, vaccinations, flea treatment, treats and toys. Click on the Sponsor This Pet link above to make your donation today. Thank you!Complete an Adoption Application!

animal.description:
Meet Rufus.

Rufus is an approximately 5 year old American Bulldog mix who was an owner surrender.  Rufus is a sweet guy with a proud strut.
We joke that he is the John Wayne of dogs, with his swagger. 
He likes attention but has his cute little "pretend" aloofness. 
He is great on a leash, enjoys exploring but also likes to just chill and enjoy the outdoors. He seems 100% housebroken. 
Rufus ignores most dogs, but no cats, small dogs (or squirrels!!) for Rufus. He would LOVE a fenced in yard! 

Rufus would work best in a home where someone is home during the day. He prefers hanging out with his person and/or family (he even prefers to sleep in the bed room with his peeps, too!) Rufus would probably be just fine with another dog of his approximate stature, with proper decompression and slow, supervised introductions, of course.

If interested in meeting Rufus please fill out an adoption application on our website.  https://www.guardiansfortheanimalsofohio.org/adoptionapplication

animal.description:
We are changing the way we do adoptions due to the virus going around.  Step one is to fill out an application at Tailsofrescue.org under dog application.  Step two will email or call and answer and ask a few questions. Step three set up a time to meet the dog at Tails of Rescue Store (981 Lake Blvd Redding CA) will be meeting OUTSIDE only.  All of our animals our in foster care at night.  We do at times use the store as daycare to keep everyone friendly with each other so not adding people not fostering into the store.  This is very different than how we have ever done adoptions so we might have a few hiccups here and there. 

Haylee is a 4-year-old female lab blend.  She has lived on a property with horses and other dogs.  NO cats!  Walks a little strong on a leash, but getting better.  The reason we have Haylee is she would see the gate open and run, but would always come home.  At the foster home, she is doing well staying in the fenced area with fencing and electric fence.  She does fine going to the store each day.  OVERWEIGHT due to sneaking puppy food.  

Haylee is spayed, chipped, heartworm negative, current on shots, kennel cough, and rabies.  Applications can be filled out at tailsofrescue.org underdog application.

If interested in the store Tuesday-Friday-Saturday from 9-12.  We are NOT a first-come-first to adopt a rescue, the best fit for the family and dog is the way we do things.  Adoption fee is $218 Spayed, Chipped, Heartworm, current on shots, and kennel cough

Welcome to fill out an application at tailsofrescue.org under dog application to get things going. We do out of town adoptions often, but will not ship animals must come to Redding for pick up.

animal.description:
* PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO* This dog has medical issues and you need to understand them before applying for him

Meet Dustin Dingo, a dachshund/beagle mix who is approximately 12-14 years old & a refined old gentleman. He likes to take his time to smell the roses! He loves cuddling and taking afternoon naps on the sofa! Dustin is good with other dogs and loves to walk around his surroundings! He is currently being cage trained and is doing well! He also is learning to potty outdoors, but must wear a diaper inside to prevent accidents. He has a lot of anxiety but his foster family is working with him and he is slowly feeling more comfortable with others and starting to show affection! Dustin speaks to his foster family by grunting & barking for attention. After all he is mostly doxie & we all know they demand to be the center of our universe.

DARE sprung Dustin from the shelter because he was in dire need of lots of medical attention which the shelter was not able to handle and we could not turn our back on this sweet fellow. We had the vet check him all over particularly regarding his renal hernia. The vet does not recommend surgery for it because at his age it would be difficult for him to recover. Dustin also has epilepsy which is being controlled with medication. Plus he recently had a dental, so his breath is nice and fresh. At his age, he has the usual diminished sight & hearing. Even with all this Dustin remains to be a very sweet boy.

Dustin is a special needs little guy and will need a family who is patient, caring & understanding of his abilities.

If you know that I am your forever dog please fill out an application at: https://daretorescue.org/adoption-application.html **Please don't forget to put my name on your application!

If you can not adopt me but would like to help DARE pay for my care while I am in their care you can donate online http://daretorescue.org/donation.html
or send check or money order made payable to DARE to:DAREPO BOX 21161
TAMPA, FL 32210
You can also contact us at info@DAREtoRescue.org
Even if you do not see a dog that matches what you're looking for, you may fill out a no obligation application and we will work to find a match for you. We receive dogs into foster care almost daily, so it is impossible to have every available or soon-to-be-available dog on the website.
1/17/21 2:04 PM

animal.description:
J.P. is an 9 lb Chihuahua who was brought in as a stray and estimated to be 10-12 yrs. young. This old man loves a sunny window, an occasional scrambled egg, and a little meander around the backyard. J.P. has extremely limited vision and will need a quiet home with no small children. Due to his vision and age he is easily startled by quick movements and has trouble in low-light situations. He expresses his fear by growling but as a toothless guy hes harmless. J.P. has recently started experiencing seizures and is now on medication that he takes a few times a day. He goes outside on a regular bathroom schedule but wears a belly band in the house to catch his senior moments. J.P. does not like the fuss of getting his "pants" off and on and he is not shy in expressing his annoyance, so shared walls of apartment living are not for him! J.P. prefers to leave playful rough housing to the younguns; however, he currently lives with another older, small, low-key chihuahua and might be comforted by the presence of another senior dog-friend. J.P. likes to know you're there if he needs ya, but prefers to relax alone in his bed, in front of the heater, or in his favorite sunny spot on the floor! The perfect home for J.P. will be one with a sense of humor, patience, and the desire to make sure this old man has everything he needs in his golden years!

The suggested adoption donation for J.P. is $200, which is TAX DEDUCTIBLE, and goes toward providing supportive services to animals in the home, as well as the high cost of vetting our animals in rescue. If you would like to welcome J.P. into your home, please begin by submitting our adoption application. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver. If you would like to learn more about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue, or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com. We invite you to visit our Facebook Page, and when you visit, please don't forget to Like our Facebook page so that you wont miss any information about our animals and events!

animal.description: Toony, as his foster mom calls him, is the best cuddler and the sweetest most handsome boy. He quickly made himself at home and has been such a great sport throughout his surgery and recovery. He was always super excited for our vet visits and got gold stars each time. He can be a pretty active boy and enjoys playing ball, running, swimming and getting outside any chance he can. But he also enjoys his sleeps, even through the loudest of thunderstorms he dreams and snores so sweetly. He's always ready for snuggles and is okay with whatever snuggle style preferred. As long as he's near you he's a happy boy. He is potty trained and crate trained, although some yummy snacks are key to getting him in there. He has shown interest in other dogs while out and absolutely loves to see his neighbor friends and walking buddies who are 2 tiny rat terriers. He isn't much of a barker and greets everyone at the door with great enthusiasm. Neptune has been such an amazing edition to our home and we know he will make someone very very happy very soon. He is an absolute joy. To contact his foster, email sonia.n.segura@gmail.com

Marley is a 12-yr old, frosted gray muzzled senior.  He is a cancer survivor that now is in need of a new home.  Marley is neutered, up to date on all his vaccinations.  He weighs 43 lbs. and is healthy.

He has been with the same family his whole life but circumstances have changed in the home where there are now a lot of children and now they are unable to keep him with them.  A family friend is able to foster him but, unfortunately, only for a short time 

He is calm, sweet and not an aggressive dog but he doesn't like noise and overstimulation.  He tends to retreat from kids and other dogs.  He is fearful of bikes and skateboards.  Due to his nervousness and anxiety, it would be best if he would be in a home with no children or other animals.

Marley has a beautiful soul and he's just trying to find his way in life like so many of us are.  He is in need of a caring long-term foster or a  long-term "I Love You Forever" home.

If interested in learning more about Marley please inquire via "Ask About Marley"

animal.description:
Ruger is a handsome Great Pyrenees.  He came to us from a home.  He has been around children and other dogs.  But we think he would do best in a kid free and dog free home. He does not do well with cats.  He would do best with someone who is around most of the time.  He is a sweetheart that just wants to be snuggled up next to his human. Any one interested in him will need to make multiple visits with him to make friends.  Ruger requires at least a 4 foot fence.

Ruger is 6 years old.  His current weight is 80 pounds.

The minimum donation for Ruger is $450.00. This includes all of his vetting. If you are interested in Ruger, please fill out an online application through our website. 

We are currently only open by appointment only. Due to the recent pandemic, we are looking at the safety of our volunteers that are there to take care of the dogs. Only serious inquiries will be considered.  

Then meet him at the shelter during adoption hours on Saturdays and Sundays 10 - 2pm. All members of the household need to meet the dog you are interested in. Vet records for any current or previous pets need to be provided. If all goes well, a home visit will be done prior to adoption.

animal.description:
I have been sponsored. Thank you Jackie Mabe for sponsoring me in December. 
Bissell is a pretty lab shepherd mix who was transferred to us from a municipal shelter. She's curious and attentive and likes to get out and go for walks. She does not seem to be a fan of other dogs, she wants all the attention. We think she is about 3-5yrs old. She can also climb a fence...her new family will need to be prepared for that. This girl LOVES people and her sweet personality outweighs all her ""challenges"". Her new family will need to be patient and help her adjust to life on the outside! We think shes best suited to be in a home with kids 8 yrs of age and over.

Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; SCPR believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.doitforthedogs.com. We are the Second Chance Pet Rescue in Grove, OK. 918-786-7630. You can email us at doitorthepets@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Little Bit, who is being fostered in Richmond, VA, is 10 years old. He is an extremely sweet and loving Peke who wants/needs to be close to his family. Little Bit is blind due to cataracts and retinal issues. He has been evaluated by a veterinary ophthalmologist but is not a candidate for corrective surgery. He is on eye drops to reduce inflammation and his adoptive family will need to continue this medication throughout his life. Little Bit can be left alone for short periods, but do not be surprised if he is barking to try to find you! He does have a bit of anxiety when left alone, but once you walk back in the house, he will be excited you are home!

Little Bit is house trained. He is good at going up the stairs but never down, so he will need your help going downstairs. Because he prefers to be with his human, he will stay outside with you as long as you like. Once he is comfortable with the area, he will wander around on either hard-scape or grass. A fenced yard is important so Little Bit can learn his boundaries while still able to roam, which he likes to do on occasion. Little Bit likes to play with chew toys (prefers squeaky), loves treats (he is very gentle when taking them) and belly rubs, but mostly to just be with you! Being blind he can get defensive around other dogs if they bark or growl. One of his favorite things to do is just sit with you while you have your morning coffee or tea. He does not mind baths but does not care for getting his hair brushed or his feet trimmed. This sweet boy is ready to take on a new chapter in his life where he can enjoy the simple things and the ability to relax with his favorite person/people.

If you are interested in more information or in adopting Little Bit, please fill out an application to adopt. http://www.potomacpekes.org/onlineapplicationadopt.htm. We accept applications from Virginia, Maryland, District of Columbia, and areas close by. We require a vet check and a home visit. Previous experience with Pekes is always a plus! Little Bit’s adoption fee is $250.00.

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE THAT WE HAVE CLOSED ADOPTIONS DUE TO THE COVID-19 VIRUS AS OUR DIRECTOR IS IMMUNOCOMPRIMISED AND UNABLE TO DO HOME CHECKS, MEET AND GREETS OR FOLLOW UP WITH OUR DOGS.

WE ARE NOT SURE HOW LONG WE WILL BE CLOSED FOR ADOPTIONS BUT IT IS VERY IMPORTANT THAT OUR TEAM PRACTICES SOCIAL DISTANCING AS WE ARE AT A HIGHER RISK OF BECOMING ILL.  

WE ARE MORE THAN HAPPY TO KEEP YOUR APPLICATION ON FILE AND CONTACT YOU ONCE WE ARE ABLE TO SAFELY RESUME THE ABOVE.

THANK YOU FOR UNDERSTANDING AND FOR WANTING TO OPEN YOUR HEART & HOME TO A RESCUE DOG IN NEED.

- ADOPTIONS TEAM



?Name:  Domino (aka - Dom)
Age:  7 Years
?Sex:   Neutered Male 
Breed:  Great Dane x Mastiff
Dogs:  No (see below)
Cats:  No
Kids:   No (see below) 
?Energy Level: Low 
Special Needs:  Cherry eye correction (August 2019).  Bilateral hip dysplasia & arthritis


Domino is another a local owner surrender.  Domino, (aka - Dom, aka - Baron von Domino), is a 7 year old Great Dane x Mastiff.  He is your typical gentle giant who loves nothing more than to sit on your lap and hang out on the sofa.  Dom exhibits many of the stereotypical Dane traits and is an expert leaner and can back right up to any unattended lap.

Domino had a condition called "Cherry Eye".  His 3rd eyelid had been prolapsed & inflamed for many years and required surgical intervention by a veterinary eye specialist.   He also had a small eyelid tumor on the same eye
as well as a mass on his shoulder.  We are happy to announce that Dom had his surgeries performed  August 2019 and has healed wonderfully!

Recently Domino has been diagnosed with bilateral hip dysplasia and he also does have arthritis in his joints.  Currently he has responded very well to his new medication (Metacam & Cartrophen injections) and is now eating a special prescription food to help with his mobility.  Domino has his consultation with a board certified orthopedic surgeon as well as a neurologist regarding his hips & gait.  Unfortunately Dom is not a surgical candidate for a total hip replacement or a femoral head osteotomy (FHO) due to his size and the risk of implantation failure.

What does that mean in future?  Domino will require daily medication lifelong.  He has been doing very well on his combination of Metacam, Gabapentin and monthly Cartrophen injections and is still the same happy loving boy he was when he arrived to our program.   

Domino's retirement home needs to be in a quiet household with NO stairs.  He is also not suited for apartment/condo living.  He loves going for walks but they do need to be short (15 minutes or less) and his new family needs to be able to restrict Dom's activity.

Dom does get along great with the other dogs in the home (ranging from medium-giant breeds) and has grown up with children.  With that being said at this time we will be in search of a home WITHOUT young kids or pets due to Domino's hip dysplasia.

What is Domino's favourite thing to do?   CAR RIDES!  As his activity now has to be restricted we take him on more car rides than long walks.  He loves nothing more than to hop into the back seat and hang his head out the window to say hi to passersby and to thank the ladies at the Tim Horton's drive thru for his Timbits.  

Please note that Dom has a fear of being alone in an enclosed space due to accidentally getting stuck in a small bathroom.  Thus far we have not been able to have him comfortable being in a crate but he does very well free range in the home.

This gentle giant sure enjoys going for car rides but most of all he LOVES snuggling with you on the couch.  He can be a bit of a picky eater but can easily be enticed with some fresh steamed veggies mixed in with his kibble.  

Is Domino the love bug you have been waiting for?  If so Adoption Applications can be found on our website at:

www.aide4paws.com

So she is ready to find a family of her very own.   Becca is a small mix....maybe Lab and not sure what else....weighs about 35 lbs. animal.description:
This handsome boy is Keen, and he is ready to find his forever!  Here are 10 things he wants his new family to know about him:

1.	I am a Bullmastiff, and I am about 4 years old. 

2.	I didn’t have a great life before rescue, so I can be very shy and timid with new people.  I sometimes bark at them, but only because I’m afraid.  My new home will need to continue working with me to help me learn to trust humans again.

3.	My ideal home would be with an adults-only family that doesn’t have many visitors to the house.  New people are scary to me, and when I’m afraid, I am not my best self. 

4.	I live with a female Cane Corso, and she’s my bestie.  It would be nice to find a home with a large, confident, and easy going female that I could be friends with.

5.	I haven’t had much experience with small dogs since I came to The Bullpen, so I don’t know how I would feel about living in a home with them.

6.	I haven’t met any cats since leaving the shelter, so I’m not sure how well I would do in a home with felines.

7.	The words that best describe me are shy, watchful, and sweet.

8.	I like to hang out with my Corso friend, sunbathe, and of course, EAT!

9.	I am housebroken, good on a leash, and I know how to use a dog door!

10.	I am fully vaccinated, heartworm negative, neutered, and microchipped. 

Ready to give Keen the forever home of his dreams?  Fill out our Adoption Application, located at www.bullpenrescue.org under the 'work with us' tab.

We highly recommend that our potential adopters fill out an online application as soon as possible, as it greatly expedites the process of finding the right dog for your situation.  

Our dogs are available for adoption nationwide but preference is given to adopters willing to do an in-person meeting.  Please understand that our dogs are not adopted on a first-come, first-serve basis, but rather we strive for a "perfect placement" so we know that they will not be failed again.

animal.description:
Biography
Hi! My name is Rocko. I'm a 6-7 year old, neutered, male Shepherd/possible Australian Kelpie mix and weigh about 60 pounds. I lived with an elderly woman and 20+ dog companions, but she couldn't take care of us anymore so we had to go the shelter.All my small dog friends were adopted, but no one took me. I was so sad and had to stay in the shelter for a long time. I was about to be euthanized, but then my foster mom rescued me!

I haven't been around people much so I'm a little nervous at first, but I really love snuggling with my foster mom and being with her all the time! I'm not quite sure what to think of kids, so I'd prefer to live in a home with all grown-ups. I get along well with my canine foster sister, but Mom says I probably shouldn't live with cats because I scare our cat when I try to play with hershe's just so fun I can't help chasing her!

I know I'll make a great companion for someone. I'm super good when I'm in the houseeven when I'm left alone! I'm house trained and don't mess with any of my foster family's stuff. I'm pretty quiet too. I'm calm and love to relax with my family inside the house, but when I go outside to play I can really runand jump over things too! Mom says I'm "agile".I'm even learning to walk on a leash! If you're looking for someone to be your loyal companion, I'm the one! Please consider me. I still have lots of years of love to give and will be so grateful to share them with you.

animal.description:
Rocky is an adult male American Bulldog, about 7 years old.  He is up to date on all his shots, neutered, and in overall good health.

Behaviorally, Rocky is a true American Bulldog.  Hes got a strong body and a strong mind, & also loves to open up & get affection from his people.  He is larger than most small children & he is not the most mindful of his size & strength, so we recommend no small children for him. 
Rocky has shown that he loves having a large yard to run & exercise himself in, he loves to chew on toys & bones, & will do anything for a yummy snack. He is fully house trained & does great alone & spending time in his crate relaxing. His absolute favorite thing is the water! He loves to play with hoses/sprinklers & even swims when he can! Rocky is a big boy full of unique personality & he is still hopeful on his search for his forever home!

Apply directly for Rocky at the link below!

https://pitofoursoulsrescue.com/our-dogs/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Nana is a beautiful, 6-year old brindle and white pittie. She is both energetic and a couch potato. She’s always ready for a walk in the woods or park and loves to cuddle up when it’s movie time.   

Nana had a rough past where she was abandoned as a puppy in a foreclosed home, and chained to a radiator back in 2014.  She needs someone who will appreciate her happy, energetic spirit and help her know she won’t ever be abandoned again. Her foster is helping her learn to receive her food more gently and working with her on housetraining, neither of which she has had in the past, but is showing progress day-by-day. Nana requires a home with adults and where she is the only animal. She handles the crate well, except of mealtime. 

She is waiting for a patient, loving home so she can put her tragic past behind her and move into a happy second chapter, where she will be a valued, loved, respected, and cherished. 

Email harescue1@aol.com to inquire. Pitbull experience required. Patience and love a must!

animal.description:
Birdie
Birdie is another precious senior pup who was found and never claimed. She is a queen and she knows it! When first found, she was scared. Her coat was horrible and she had a tumor growing on her tail. She has since had surgery to remove the tumor and the majority of her tail. The tumor was cancerous but it is a slow growing cancer. We could do radiation treatments but putting her through the agony of that is something we don't want to do. Her outlook is about 3 years and that is if her heart doesn't worsen before then. Birdie was also found to have some heart failure. Now since that awful tumor is gone (the removal had poor margins) and since being placed on 3 medications for her heart, Birdie is thriving. She is now about 11 years old (5/2020). She is in a foster home where she wants to be boss. Literally. She runs all the other dogs off so all of the attention can be hers. She loves people but she can also be bossy with small children. Birdie is very vocal when something displeases her majesty. She is also housetrained, she has to sleep in the bed with you, and she prefers to go on all of you trips in the car. Birdie is looking for a new home but until the absolute perfect one is found, she is safe in foster care. If you're looking for some spunk in your life and you have a heart for seniors, let us know! Date of Intake: 7/3/19, 5/20/2020 (due to passing of adopter)
Birdie is located in foster care. Email us at Dogs@maumellefoa.org for more information. Online adoption applications available at www.Maumellefoa.org. Our adoption fee is $80. Included in the fee is shots, sterilization, microchip, dogs are given a dewormer at time of intake, placed on monthly flea/tick preventative, if heartworm negative then they are placed on heartworm preventative, if heartworm positive then they are treated once an adoption finalized.
Please note regarding the application to adopt: Personal references, landlord reference and veteranarian references / vetting history will be checked. All past and current pets must have been or must be up to date on vaccines and given heart worm preventative unless otherwise indicated by your veteranarian. If you use multiple vet clinics, please include them all.
Find Maumelle Friends of the Animals on Facebook!

animal.description:
Asher is one of the most interesting and deep individuals we have the honor of spending time with. Passionate. Confident. Ambitious. Rebellious. Genius. Risk taker. Thrill seeker. Charisma master. Charm keeper. Energy reader. Athlete. Devoted companion like no other. 70lbs. A little under 2 years old. Bull Terrier. Seeking a life partner who understands the breed, is equally looking for an actual someone to share their life with, to commit, explore, learn, love and slay together, Forever. Someone patient, someone leading an active lifestyle. Someone into agility or nose work. Someone who makes their dog the center of their universe. Someone patient, committed with time to explore the unknown. This dog could could be taught to write masterpiece novels, build bridges, fly planes and be the detective necessary to any cause. Not a family dog. Not a dog to entertain your other dog. Best as only animal in the house. He’s in it for a love of a lifetime with his human and he thrives at having a job. When he locks his eyes in yours, vulnerability wakes to a new meaning.

Animals can be viewed by appointment only. We ask that you review our adoption information AND fill out an adoption application prior to setting an appointment so we have all your information and you understand our adoption procedures - you can do so online here.     

Please feel free to email us or call us anytime for additional information on any of our animals - info@mcprescue.org or 312-388-3928. Our typical adoption fee varies based on the age of the dog at the time of rescue: Under the age of 1 years old is $500; 1-5 years old is $400; over the age of 5 is $300. Fees include vaccinations, microchip, deworming and other vetting as needed. Our adoption process includes an application, reference check and home visit.

animal.description:
Apply to Adopt Me!

Look at this happy boy! Raj is a 2-year-old, 70-lb. beefcake pitty mix who is hoping desperately for a forever home. Pictures just don't do this boy justice. Raj is the sweetest ball of energy that needs a foster, a foster to adopt, or an adopter to take him under his or her wing. He would do best with a gentle authoritative handler who can set boundaries, encourage confidence and provide structured stability. We prefer an adult-only home, although Raj would be fine with older preteen/teens but so much for toddlers. He is a high-energy pup and would not want to hurt anyone accidentally because he didn't know his own strength. He is a bit jumpy and boisterous because he is ready to play anytime you will let him. As you can see in his video, he loves playing with his fur sibling Champ. Raj needs a highly breed-experienced owner - this is a must. Raj would do well (after slow introductions) with another dog who wouldn't mind his rambunctious personality, and would need someone with the ability to handle him with another dog. Raj needs a minimum 6-ft. fenced-in yard to run around in. Cats are a no for Raj. His ability to trust is amazing when people from his past have given him every reason not to. Raj is so deserving of the love and stability he has never had before. He is housebroken, crate trained and nondestructive. This wonderful boy is currently being fostered by a trainer.

animal.description:
Remy was found as a stray in Anaconda and was transferred to Pintler Pets on 10/18/19. He is about two years old, a red tick coonhound. He is athletic, curious and very affectionate. He is quite sensitive and suffers here at the Rescue because he so wants to be with his person. His adopter will need to be careful of his jealousy with other dogs in the home, but this can be managed. He is able to climb chain link fencing, so wood/vinyl would be ideal. Plastic sheeting could be placed on the bottom 3 ft, of a chain link fence to prevent him getting a toe-hold. If you want an adoring companion, who loves to please you, Remy is for you.

All our dogs are spayed/neutered, de-wormed, vaccinated appropriate for their age, vaccinated for kennel cough, and micro-chipped. Puppies (under 6 months) are $225.00; puppies (6 months to 2 years) are $175.00, dogs (over 2 years) are $150 and senior dogs (7 years or older) are $60.00.

animal.description:
Meet Gretchen!

ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

Gretchen is an approximately five year old Pit bull. She weighs 68lbs. Gretchen is a sweet girl who loves people and dogs. Sadly, she has very  bad knees that can’t be fixed. Gretchen doesn’t seem to mind though.. she loves to go for walks and is very easy to walk. Sometimes after a walk she can get a little stiff, but a one mile walk is a breeze for her. She should not live in a home with lots of stairs. Single level is best for her. She needs a securely fenced yard, not an apartment.

Gretchen loves Kongs and sometimes gets the zoomies. She’s so happy! She doesn’t like being crated but is not destructive when left alone. She is currently living with another female Pit bull  in her foster and they love to play together. Gretchen growls when she  plays and that can be scary for another dog. It depends on their comfort level.

Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. 

If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please use the following link and complete our Adoption Application. You can either scan your completed application and email it to us at: info@indigorescue.org, or you can fax it to us at: 888-502-7660.
The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser: https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user-680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf
If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.
PLEASE NOTE: Indigo Rescue only adopts to homes within 30 miles of Beaverton because our volunteers deliver all of our dogs to their adoptive homes. We work very hard to create a family of our Indigo Rescue adopters because we want to be close enough to help in case there are any problems. We want everyone to be happy and successful!

**ALL of our dogs, puppies, cats, kittens and rabbits come vaccined to their age, spayed/neutered and microchipped.

Thank you for your interest in adopting and saving a life.

animal.description:
Courtesy Post – Rayna has been with the rescue group Paws Across Oswego for a few months. She came to them after the local Shelter reached out for help finding out why Rayna was blind…everyone hoping that since she was still young she might somehow get better.

Two of the rescue volunteers took Rayna on the long drive to Albany to have an MRI and see the specialists there.  It was found that she had two hematomas on her brain from an injury. One that must have happened when she was a very small puppy.  Although it was found she was in no pain, and will not get worse, she will never regain her vision.

But that doesn’t stop this beautiful girl. Rayna loves to run and play in the large yard in the grass and loves all the volunteers here.
She will need a very special home that understands the needs of a blind dog and a fenced in yard. But blind dogs adapt very quickly to their surroundings. So don’t let that stop you from adopting!  She is an absolute sweetheart and deserves a wonderful home.

Please reach out directly to Paws Across Oswego for more information about Adopting Rayna.

http://pawsacrossoswegocounty.com/adoption_information/

Kavalier is very timid of people but is warming up to them.  She listens very well and knows her name and knows when called to come in the house.  She does well with other dogs, as that is where she gets her confidence from.  Kavalier would thrive in a home with other dogs and a backyard.  She would not be a good lone dog nor would she be a good apartment dog.  When she goes for walks, she must have another dog to go along with, otherwise she is very frightful and "bucks" on the leash; but once another dog goes along for the walk, she is great.

If you'd like more information about me or to setup a Meet-and-Greet, please send CiMAR an email so my Foster Mom can contact you.  You can also find more pictures of me on their website:  http://www.cuzimatter.org/adopt-a-dog

Duke, 6yrs, Male, Cane Corso, Brindle, 150#

Duke is an amazing boy, but he is all Corso. Only homes with guardian breed experience will be considered for adoption. True to his breed, He is protective of his home and people. Loyal to a fault, he loves his humans. Though he loves kids, due to some resource guarding behavior, he needs a home without young children. 

Duke is very good on his basic obedience and he is crate trained. He does well with other even temperament dogs and is generally  pretty easy going guy. He would be best in a home with no small dogs or cats. 

His adoptive home must have a 6 foot privacy fence, to keep him safe. And must be (within 50 miles) local to the Saint Louis metropolitan area. 

Duke's adoption donation is $450.00 and he is up to date and fully vetted. 

Interested adopters must submit an adoption application through our website, steppingstonebully.org to be considered.

animal.description:
Sugar is a 13 year old, 46 pound Beagle/hound mix who is a friendly girl and adores people. She seems to like everyone, though, as a mature lady, she would rather not be around active babies and little tykes in her home. She prefers well mannered grown ups.

She still loves to take walks and is good on the leash unless that Beagle nose pulls her towards something that smells really great.

She is a sweet girl and has an easy going nature, typical of what makes seniors so precious.

She does still like to play with a tennis ball, though!

Sugar holds her pee and poo for when it is time to go outside, no accidents for this lady.

Sugar is past her playful years so wants to be an only dog in her new home, especially since that is what she is used to. She is not that fond of other dogs anyway.

Sugar is a sweetheart who really deserves a loving retirement home. She promises to love you so much and says she is not that much trouble, an easy keeper.

No cats in her new home - she thinks they are critters to hunt.

Apply online at www.triadspca.org. Sugar is staying in a wonderful foster home and we would be happy to arrange for you to meet her if you call us at 336-375-3222.

animal.description:
Ireland is the silly sibling of Ian and Ingrid.
The trio came to Briggs after being rescued from a hoarding situation.
All three of these sweet pups are shy with new people and situations but they are making positive steps each day.
Ireland seems to be the more outgoing of the bunch and can be very friendly once she gets to know you.
She also helps her brother Ian along by helping him feel more confident.
They all love to play with one another and will come over for a pet from their trusted caregivers.
We would like them to go to a quieter household to help them continue on a path to feeling more secure.
They may also benefit from having a more confident dog in the home as a companion.
We will also be requiring 6ft high securely fenced yard for all three of these siblings.
These siblings are looking for a loving and patient forever home to call their own.
If you are interested in adopting Ireland please contact us soon.

animal.description:
Archie is in our Forever Care Program. Dogs in our Forever Care Program are either hospice or require ongoing medical care. Every Pet's Dream is committed to providing for Forever Care Dogs for the remainder of the dog's life. Although these dogs are no longer available to adopt you can still help them by making a one-time donation or a monthly donation, for their care.

Please help us save more dogs like Archie.

paypal.com/us/fundraiser/charity/2384371

#100Rescued! Every Pet's Dream is so happy to introduce you to our 100th Rescue! Meet Archie!!

Archie loves everyone he meets. He is good with dogs of all sizes. Archie loves sunbathing and wants nothing more than to cuddle with his humans. He's got so much personality and is one of the most loving dogs. We were heartbroken when the cancer diagnosis came. However, we are thrilled that Archie is truly at home with us and loved by the entire family.

We don't know how long Archie was been neglected before we rescued him and he came to us in bad shape, but we know he will never be neglected again.

Rescued July 2018

Archie is 11 years old and 60 pounds. 1/24/21 1:12 AM

>>>Axl is an 8 yr old, amazing boy who gets along with other dogs AND kids!! He will be the perfect addition to any family. Axl is a very sweet dog. He really enjoys getting his belly rubbed and his favorite pasttime is to chase water from the hose in the backyard.

Axl is a bit of a nervous dog with scary noises, including fireworks and thunder. He does best wearing a Thundershirt during any storms.

animal.description:
** Pls READ: Blossom is VERY shy! She needs
 1) Another young playful dog in the home &
 2) Someone who has experience with fearful dogs. 
Pls folks- take the time to read the bios.  Blossom & her siblings are awesome dogs but it will take time before you see the fun side that we see

Blossom is a 1.5year-old Australian Shepherd mix. This sweet girl is very shy with new people. She is great great great with other dogs of all sizes. She is currently in a foster home with 2 Chihuahuas and a couple large mutts and is having a great time!. 

She came from a hoarder case where unlike other hoarder cases these dogs were treated very well and were loved...There were just too many of them and they were not socialized with other people during that crucial puppy stage.  Because she is so shy and kids can be loud, scary and leave doors open, we are looking to place her in a home with adults only.  

Blossoms ideal home would be with:

1) 1-2 people in a house (not a lot of people coming in & out) No kids

2) MUST have another dog. Preferably one young & playful like her. She doesn't need just a companion but also a playmate.

3) Must have a  6ft fence that is completely secure. (we do yard checks) 

4) a LOT of love & patience to give & you will find it given back once she's comfortable

It seems like we are asking a lot but we know we will find her the right home. if you ever meet her you'll understand why we have to be picky where she goes.  She truly is a total love once she feels comfortable with you.

If you have a loving atmosphere & another dog for her to learn from please fill out an application. We would love to get this girl into a foster or forever home.  https://www.muttsinneed.org/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Nova is a 46 pound,, 6 year old German Shepherd Mix. She is happy and loves running around in the yard playing with her foster humans!   She is always smiling and acts much younger than her biological age!   She's a very sweet girl looking for her forever family to love and adore!

Like many rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

I'm an active girl that likes to run and play, so I'm looking for a home with a fenced yard and a person to play frisbee with me!  I like one-on-one attention, so I really don't want to share my home with another dog or cat.  I also don't have a history with little kids so I can't go to a home with kids under 7 (per rescue policy).   However, all that aside, I'm a happy, smiley, loving girl.  I'm also intelligent so you can train me.  We could have so much fun playing and training!  If you're looking for a smart, pretty, lovable girl who doesn't have to share you with any other pets, ask about me.  I can't wait to meet you!

animal.description:
Fancy STATS:

Approximate age     3 years             
Approximate weight     51 pounds        
Breed (s)      Bulldog/pit mix--possibly Dogo Argentino mix, but who knows for certain?  Stark white with tiny black spots.   
Spayed or neutered?     Spayed

Good with:       
kids?        Possibly, but proper introductions are necessary. 
strangers?      Fancy must be properly introduced to whomever she meets.  Once she knows you, she’s very sociable and friendly.
other dogs?      Possibly, but only with proper introductions.      
cats?     No cats.   Fancy has a strong prey drive.   
On leash?    With the training she’s been provided, Fancy is very good with the e-collar, walks well on heel, and has learned all the “sit,” “down,” “place,” “kennel” and other commands.
Housetrained?    Yes.        
Crate trained?      Yes.          
Paper trained?     No.


Fancy was brought to the New York Animal Care Centers (NYACC) by her owner as a surrender in April 2019, August 2019.  They said the landlord wasn't allowing her any longer.  She then developed Kennel Cough then was placed on the At-Risk List where she was almost euthanized.

Someone saw her and wanted to foster her.  She didn't do well at the shelter in that environment at all and was deteriorating.  


Preferred forever home for your foster?  Fancy would do well with a family with no small children and without strangers coming and going.  No cats.  She is dog selective, and with proper introduction may do okay with a dog on the smaller side--she did okay at Board and Train with a number of dogs.  She will learn to meet new people, but that has to be worked through in order that she can safely get to know new folks.  She is puppy-ish, fun, and has a lot of energy, so her new owners will want to play with her, take her on walks, etc.  She loves the flirt pole, loves chasing.  She is an extremely smart and adoring dog once she gets to know you, but she takes a while to warm up to strangers, so it’s best that she go to a quiet home.  She loves the outdoors and would do great in a home with property, though fences cannot be trusted, as she will either scale them or dig under them.  She would love to be an only pet but could be tested with a second dog.


Interesting quirks/behaviors:  

Fancy is extremely smart and loving, and because of these qualities, she is prone to separation-type anxiety and so must be kept active, stimulated.  She literally leaps for joy, and can from a sitting position go over 6 feet--this is something we’ve discouraged, but it’s also fun to watch and okay if it’s allowed only during playtime.  Once she gets to know you, you will never feel love this strong again from a dog.  She is also extremely beautiful with her shocking white coat--looks like a unicorn when out in the sun (but without the horn).

Issues:  She has anxiety issues that can veer toward separation-anxiety and, if not kept on the protocol she’s learned at training, could turn into fear-based aggression.  Allied Training has agreed to work with the new owner, so all this will be clear.  She’s also smart and no couch potato, so she’ll need play, walks and stimulation--once that’s in place, though, she is happy to curl up by your feet wherever you are.

Fancy is so loving it can’t but touch a person’s heart.  She’s also just a bundle of puppy-like, playful fun.  An incredible dog.

animal.description:
Addie and Maddie were saved off death row in a high kill Texas shelter.  The 1 year old Rhodesian mix sisters could barely walk from old back leg/hip injuries that didn't heal correctly.

Fast forward a few months with medication (carprofen), CBD Oil and joint supplements and these girls are almost Bionic!  Addie has now been adopted.

Maddie for a very specific home due to their background.  She is great with people once she gets to trust you.  Little apprehensive of strangers and their intentions at first.  Remember, these are dogs that came from living on the streets and having to fend and provide for themselves.   She has a taill that will wag for hours!

Ok now the real stuff that you need to know about Maddie.  She is also pretty crafty and a 5 or 6 ft chain link fence is a breeze for her to Houdini out of (trust me I know .. I said they were now feeling bionic remember LOL).  No other small animals (cats, chickens, rabbits ect).  

She would be happiest with a large, wide open area to spend her days laying out in the sunshine.  Lots of acreage and a wireless system / electric fence may be ideal for her.  She also needs a building that allows access to 24/7 that contains heat in the winter and A/C in the summer.  She has no fur and can't spend the winter outside, period, end of sentence.  

We don't ever adopt our dogs to be outside dogs, and it is the same with Maddie.  We want them to be loved family members, but also know what will make her happy as well, so we may be looking for the impossible, but I hope not.  I hope in time with the right family she will be comfortable in a home .. but I understand she may never get there.  

Maddie is up to date on vaccines, spayed, heart worm negative, on preventions and micro chipped.  She does ok on leash and in the car when crated.  She is about 40 lbs currently and will stay medium sized.

Maddie is currently located in Tennessee and the adoption fee is $150 each  The first step in our process is submitting the application.  We are happy to set up a meet and greet once an application has been approved. If you would like to adopt Maddie please fill out our online adoption application at http://safehaventn.com/ .

animal.description:
Meet Gru! Energetic, loving, craves a leader.

It might take Gru a bit to trust you, but he does take note on who genuinely invests time in him. Once you do, you become his entire world. Gru is an insecure guy so it is really critical that his new owner lead him, show him, calmly guide him. When he is told what to do, he is obedient and the most loyal, eager to please personality you'll come across. He takes time, but boy is it worth it! He'll do just about anything for those that provide him calm direction. Constantly looking at them for direction. It's beautiful! 

Gru comes with a fan club! Our team will show you exactly how he communicates and provide you with the tools and support you need. We plan to give his new human the road map for success and life long support! We got your back! And his. For life. 

Gru does get along with other dogs and has lived with them. He doesn't crave to engage them, but he is OK if they are there. Being an only child though may just be what he needs for success. He's open to options here though it would need to be friendly confident dog that he can follow and learn from. 

To schedule an appointment to learn more about Gru and to see if he might be a good fit for your home, give us a call at 775-800-1906.

animal.description:
Meet Amos! Quiet, curious, independent and easy going. 

Amos is looking for a single person or quiet couple that would love nothing more than to have a buddy around and provide an older dog a loving home. Amos takes a little time to get you know you and to trust. He comes from a pretty rough past so he prefers to be ignored at first, until he's comfortable. The more time you spend, the more comfortable he gets. Now, we get to see him play and run around in circles with excitement! It's pretty awesome and a huge change from how he felt when he arrived. 

Amos will be pretty mellow in the home and grateful for a consistent meal and a soft bed. A spacious yard, walks in the hills and a person he can call his own would be his dream life. He has an independent side for awhile, however once he knows you, he really does begin to love and show more of himself. Because he doesn't jump in strangers laps or hand out affection to everyone... you know you're "in" when you start to see him offering it up to you. 

We absolutely admire his strength and mental toughness. He made it! And we couldn't be happier. 

To schedule an appointment to meet Amos and learn more about him, please call 775-800-1906.

animal.description:
Brody is a gorgeous white and fawn colored retriever mix who weighs about 65 pounds, is neutered, up to date on vaccines and microchipped. He is estimated to be about 5-6 yrs old. Brody gets along with other dogs but not interested in playing and is a little socially awkward. He is hesitant at first and will need time and patience from his new family. He will need a home that can work on his manners in a completely positive way and manage his quirky ways. A fully fenced in yard is Required as he is very skittish when walking outside of his comfort zone area. If you are looking for a walking partner or someone to take to the park he is NOT your dog. An experienced pet parent(s) is needed for Brody as he has some resource guarding issues that need to be monitored. He is a vocal dog and tries to communicate with sounds that can be misunderstood at first. He is the type of dog that needs time to trust his human before bonding and is leery of new situations. He has come a long way in his foster home but will need continued reinforcement and a very committed home. We believe older kids or no kids would be best for him since he is still learning boundaries. Preferably a low key home without a lot of visitors or activity.

Interested in adopting me? To fill out an application visit 3 Hearts 4 Paws

Are you a runner/jogger?  Need a running buddy that can hang with you...even if training for a marathon? Sirius just might be the boy for you!

Sirius is a handsome "tuxedo" lab who is around 3 years old and came to us as an unclaimed stray.  He needs room to run and an active family committed to working with him and getting him the exercise he needs. 

He spent some time at Camp Bow Wow and loves to play with other pups and loves people. Being a younger dog, he has a lot of energy and still has some manners to learn. He does ok with other high energy playful dogs, but is often too much for more laid back dogs to handle. 

When working with a trainer, he did well when he earned a treat for good behavior! He can sit, lay down, and shake. He needs work on the leash, but did better with treats. 

He needs a little help with potty training but taking a little time with him in his new house by letting him out often and giving praise, he'll figure it out. He is a smart, tall, lanky puppy and he is always a happy boy. Sirius will need an owner that works with him and he will be loyal to the end! 

He loves food and is very food motivated, so continued training and working with him should be easy.  He also loves to cuddle up with his person and snuggle!   He is neutered, microchipped, up to date on shots and current with heartworm and flea and tick preventives. 

Adoption fee is $300.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact:  Kim @ 507-351-6647 or k.balder@hotmail.com

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. 

There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.
