animal.description:
RJ is a three year old, 65 pound Staffordshire Terrier who has had a rough go of things having spent his youth in and out of the shelter system.  He could really use a turn of good luck. Most recently, RJ has been staying with a dog trainer and has excelled in his lessons.  He knows all the foundational obedience skills, many tricks, walks well on a leash, and only barks when someone comes to the door.

RJ will not annoy you with “needy-ness”.  Unlike some dogs who follow you around and beg for attention at every turn, RJ is content to lay on his bed by the fire when he is not otherwise engaged.  Snuggle sessions with RJ come only after months of trust are built and even then, physical affection is on his terms.  He’s wary of strangers so patience is a must.  Once you are in his circle of trust however, he can pour on the charm.  

We are looking for a dog savvy home for RJ and an owner whose heart is in rescue. We are not entirely clear on what he’s experienced in his young life but are committed to finding him a quiet home with a healthy routine where he can feel safe from now on.  We are imagining a single person who works from home, or a couple, with no other pets or perhaps another female dog.  RJ would like to be in a rural or semi-rural area with the ability to get out in nature regularly. He would not do well in an apartment or in a busy urban area.

RJ does enjoy playing with other dogs and would be most happy if he had a few female dog-friends to play with regularly.  Dog-dog play with girlfriends is by far his favorite form of exercise. He is not a dog park type of dog.   His exercise requirements are medium – a couple of long walks a day and some off-leash play should suffice most days, with some occasional bigger adventures thrown in.  As mentioned, he’s a big fan of positive reinforcement training.

RJ is in good health and is physically fit – a strikingly handsome specimen!  He is looking for a special person to bond with and to help him be successful in life, and in love.

RJ's adoption fee includes spay/neuter, basic vaccinations, rabies vaccination, and flea/tick treatment.

You can find his application here:

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

Questions? Contact us at connellpetrescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
Midas was pulled from MDAS in 2017 as a little buddy.  In December 2017, at approximately 6 months old, his foster mom adopted him.  To our surprise, in June of 2019, we were notified via email and phone that Midas was found in Northern Alabama.  After piecing together the timeline of events following his adoption thanks to the kind woman who had been taking care of him since the end of 2018 (we didn't know he was in Alabama), dealing with the uncooperative adopter from 2017, getting him vetted in Alabama, and arranging transport, Midas made his way from Alabama back to South Florida on July 4th thanks to very helpful transporters.  After hanging out with a few different fosters, Midas joined the 12th session of the Pawsitive Direction program.  Midas deserves a LOVING FOREVER home.

** Approximately 3 year old Pit Bull mix

** Neutered, UTD on shots, and microchipped

** VERY dog friendly.  Participated in large playgroups at Trail of Hope Rescue (they generously housed him for us for 1 1/2 weeks before the session started because his temporary foster mom went out of town) and has been used this session to teach another dog boundaries and how to properly interact with other dogs.  Midas is patient, tolerant, and gives proper corrections to other dogs when needed which are awesome behavior traits.  He does not resource guard toys from other dogs (We don't know if he resource guards food from other dogs because we don't feed them together. Each dog eats in his/her own kennel out of respect for every dog in the program.).

** Kid friendly

** NO CATS ( we will NOT adopt to a home with inside or outside cats)

** Medium energy.  LOVES balls whether playing fetch with one or just walking around with one in his mouth.  Enjoys hanging out in pools and playing with his canine friends.  LOVES to snuggle and be loved on, too.

** Very sweet, loving, and so handsome

** House/kennel trained

** Graduated fully obedience trained, AKC Canine Good Citizen (CGC) ready, and PhD in Canine Life and Social Skills (CLASS) ready

Interested in adopting amazing Midas?  Please contact Nicole (561) 723-8197 or email loxanimalrescuecomm@gmail.com

animal.description: Meet Kingston! Kingston is a 2 year old 100 lb Cane Corso/shepherd mix that entered our rescue from an over crowded city shelter in the fall of 2019. Kingston was initially treated for heart worm and still has insatiable thirst from prednisone treatment. He entered the rescue underweight and was likely a former backyard dog just based on his mannerisms and behaviors.  Kingston has a very playful temperament but he's a big boy, prone to guarding and he spooks easy.  He is not be suitable to live with small children.  Kingston walks well on a leash and knows basic commands. He is food motivated and has good recall. Kingston is dog friendly but likely will attempt to rough house rougher than most dog's comfort. Kingston is a high caliber dog, he's rough around the edges and is not suitable for an inexperienced owner/handler or even the average dog owner. His ideal home is without children or cats and with another dog or two and an experienced/ savvy owner. If you currently have a dog and are interested in adopting Kingston a fenced yard is required for him to live comfortably in a multi-dog household. Kingston is up to date on vaccines, neutered, microchipped, and crate trained. If you are interested in meeting and potentially adopting Kingston fill out an application on our website, bighairanimalrescue.com

animal.description:
KATNISS IS IN DESPERATE NEED OF A FOSTER IN TX or in NE/CO/WY THAT IS EXPERIENCED

Currently located in the Dallas area but we can get her pretty much anywhere for the right home!

This is Katniss

To look at this smiling and peppy girl, you would have no idea that Katniss' story is a heartbreaking one. She was turned into the shelter with an open stab wound on her back and wax burns on her head and face. The owner who turned her in said that she was in a fight with another dog (a chihuahua) and to stop it they stabbed her and dumped hot wax on her, (WHAT). The shelter took her to an emergency vet who closed her wound. She was a shelter favorite and everyone just loved her so she was able to stay at the shelter long past her euthanasia date but eventually she became urgent. She dog tested well at the shelter on multiple occasions including multiple play groups and without knowing the situation with the fight it's hard to know what exactly happened or who was at fault. 

Katniss had a foster step up however an incident occurred at his home within the first couple days of being there with one of his dogs we have no idea what happened. After a long and dramatic ordeal Katniss was dropped off at boarding where she has been since. We had been networking her privately but at this point it's clear that she will need the public's help to get her into a foster or adoptive home. 

What does Katniss Need?
A home with no other dogs or someone who is experienced enough to crate and rotate and slow introductions. 

Katniss' Likes
Katniss loves people, even though she has all the reason to hate them. She is cuddly and sweet and epically charismatic. 

Katniss' Dislikes
I don't want to say she dislikes all dogs because I truly don't think that's correct. She has been dog tested in boarding and in the shelter and was fine. We have no desire to risk setting her up to fail and that's why we are looking for an only dog home, or an experienced owner who can crate and rotate do slow introductions and work with her as she deserves. We do have some trainers who we will happily pay to help. We are looking for a home without small dogs, cats or other small furry critters.

Katniss' Health
Katniss is up to date on vaccines and her stab wound has healed well. She has someone who is happy to take her to be spayed ahead of her move to her foster/adopter. 

Katniss deserves the world. She has really been dealt a bad hand in this world and truly deserves a life with a family of her own. To meet her is to love her, you don't stay alive at this high kill shelter that long past her euthanasia date just because. Katniss is wishing and waiting.

Can you be her miracle?

If you are interested in fostering or adopting Katniss please contact us ASAP! We want to see her thrive!

animal.description:
Please note: B’See has had many applicants, but I am holding out for someone with a large yard (at least an acre) enclosed by an “invisible fence” and a situation where he will not be left alone all day.

B’See is a three-year old neutered border collie/hound mix who doesn’t have an aggressive bone is his body! HE WEIGHS ABOUT 59 LBS.   What he does have is an abundance of affection and  high spirits.  He also has one aim in life--to light out for the territory.  HE NOT ONLY NEEDS AN ABOVE GROUND FENCED-IN YARD; HE NEEDS AN INVISIBLE FENCE!  If he doesn't have an electric back up, he'll climb up and over any fence and light out for part unknown. 

Otherwise, B’See is a dream dog.  He’s crate trained, house trained, walks well on a leash, rides well in the car and most important, he’s extremely affectionate.— a real leaner.   BUT because he’s got some hound in him,  B’See MUST HAVE A SECURELY FENCED IN YARD.

He does like to chew hard, wooden objects, which probably means he's still quite young.  Fortunately, he accepts corrections very well and will willingly let you redirect him from one poorly chosen object to another acceptable chewing object---like a raw meaty bone or kong.

Do feel free to call me and talk about B'See.

animal.description:
This beautiful girl is Lilly!

Lilly is a female, Blue Nose Pitbull rescue who is estimated to be 3-5 years old. She is very healthy, spayed, vaccinated, and potty trained.

She knows the commands sit, come, lay down, roll over, and high five. She is very playful and affectionate. She loves to give high fives, play fetch, and tug of war. She wants to be lying down next to you whenever she's given the chance. She's so attentive and curious about everything her human is doing.

Lilly is very shy and timid, but very friendly with people. She does need time to adjust to new situations/people. When she meets new people, she paces back and forth and may bark quietly out of nervousness. Once a new person sits on a couch, she'll run up to you and start to kiss you, give you high fives, and allow you to pet her. She is a very sweet dog who cares about doing well.

She's had a very rough life prior to being rescued about two years ago. The shelter that Lilly was rescued from was overflowing with dogs. She was attacked by other dogs at the shelter twice in the same week, and as a result, she has scars on her front arms and face. Because of her history, she is very nervous around other dogs and will act aggressively.

She is scared of kids (attempts to run away/pulls on leash), and has never been in a home with kids. She needs a loving and experienced owner who has a yard and no other pets.

If you think Lilly is for you, please fill out an application at www.doggiebonez.com so that we can schedule a meet and greet. She is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short and/or long term doggie foster families. We greatly appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort and safety of a home and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if needed) etc. If you are interested please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.UPDATE

In January 2020, we found an injury on Princess Mia's abdomen and took her in to the vet for stitches. We don't know how she got the injury -- she was in a space all to herself, so it couldn't have been caused by another dog. Her shelter was a 12' x 12' horse stall with wood walls, and the stall's small yard has woven wire fencing -- no barbed wire to get caught on. So it's a mystery. The vet put in a drain tube and stressed the importance of keeping the injury clean, so we moved Princess into the house. She stayed in our "dog infirmary" on her own, using a small fenced patio for her potty needs. As she got better, she started going over the patio fence (which is only 3' tall) to explore our fenced yard. After a few weeks of recovery, we took her out to a small pasture, thinking she would be very happy to get back to a pasture and have more freedom. We were wrong. First chance she got, Princess followed us back to the house, and she has lived inside ever since. She is still extremely shy, but she is getting a little braver every day. At first, she hid in a bedroom closet. Then she started coming into the kitchen. Finally she ventured into the family room. Now, Princess spends most days on the floor next to Lynnette's desk, and she spends her evenings next to the sofa. She goes outside to potty, and occasionally walks around, checking things out in the yard, but generally, after a few minutes, she comes right back to the same door she went out, ready to come back in the house. So after a lifetime of living in the pasture and not being handled by humans, Princess has decided to retire and start a second career as a house pet. 

ORIGINAL INTAKE STORY

Princess Mia has been guarding goats her whole life, until her human died. Like so many people, her owner was the kind who thought you just put a puppy in the pasture and let her do her job. No human interaction. No veterinary care. The natural result of this outdated way of thinking is that the dog has a variety of health issues and has no reason to trust humans. It was a real challenge for local rescuers and animal control in the Waco area to wrangle Princess into the truck so she could go to the vet. But thank heavens they were persistent. Thanks also for the amazing Dr. Meier and her team at All Heart Veterinary Center, who sedated Princess in the truck, to reduce the stress of being moved out of the truck and into the clinic. Princess was spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and heartworm-tested (she is positive but is being treated). She also had puncture wounds on her mouth/cheek from an unknown source, so Dr. Meier cleaned those wounds and stitched up the larger ones. Princess is now settled in one of our barn kennels, where she appreciates the canned food, which I'm sure is easier on her injured mouth, and which is great for hiding her meds. She hasn't yet tried out her brand new bed, but hopefully she'll figure that out soon enough. We're encouraged that she lets us pet her every time we go inside the kennel. Some dogs who have been raised hands-off as she was, will not tolerate human touch. We will take our time with this sweet girl, hoping to earn her trust.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Birdie is a senior girl from down south. She is an absolute sweetheart with lots of love to give. She is always happiest around people and LOVES to have your attention. Birdie enjoys exploring outside and would love a fenced-in yard to do that! She gets along with dogs of all sizes but would be perfectly content as your one and only so that she doesn't have to share your attention.

Don't let her age sway you, she has energy to play and take short walks and loves to snuggle up with you afterward.

She is a great cuddle buddy, has the cutest snore, and is treat motivated. Birdie does have some hip/joint pain when she goes to sit down but moves around really well otherwise. She also does not need to be crated as she does not like it.

Birdie should go to a home where her humans are home all the time. She's older and leaving her alone for 8 hours a day is not ideal for her.

Birdie can be protective of her surroundings and her humans, so new people coming over just need to slowly let her come to you on her terms. If she doesn't know you she does not like you touching her on the head/face area. If you have treats she will warm right up and once you have earned her trust, she will love you forever and willingly accept all pets and belly rubs you have to offer!

Birdie enjoys her stuffed animal toys as well as peanut butter filled bones. She doesn't ask for much. She simply wants her furever family to love her unconditionally.

**Please note we do not adopt to Canada due to border issues and breed specific legislation.Adoption donation includes Spay/Neuter, UTD on Vaccinations, deworming, and flea treatment.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Update- Sweetie has seizures. She will need to be on medication for the rest of her life. She will need blood work every 6 months so it is not cheap and she cannot go somewhere where someone is not at home to get her immediately to the hospital if needed.I came to the ranch way overweight. The nice ladies there worked with me and my sons to get us trim and healthy. Man did we start to have a lot of fun when we could run around easy!!! Lets just say we got our 'groove' back. We might even be called a little mischevious :) We LOVE to cuddle all 3 of us together in a pile and we have a lot of fun playing in the play yards! The ladies have promised we will get to stay together and have a fenced yard. However long it takes 2nd Chance says we deserve to be valued and kept healthy :)If you are looking for a Grumble fill out an app and we will be in touch!Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

Gwen was brought to C.A.R.E. after being found as a stray. She was very thin, heartworm positive, and had severe skin issues. Her medical needs were taken care of and she was spayed. Gwen has now packed on a few pounds and she's waiting for her perfect home.

Gwen needs to be in a home without any other pets. She is food and treat aggressive with other dogs.

This large, strong girl is looking for a single owner, or a family with teens, who has had previous large dog experience and will respect her need for slow introductions to a new environment. She requires someone able to set boundaries and handle her with firm, loving guidance.

Gwen can be very sweet and loves to play, if you are on her list favorite people. She is picky when it comes to choosing people to love. Possible adopters should be prepared to visit her several times in order to convince her that you are deserving of her affection. We know that she is well worth the effort!

animal.description:
Meet Annabel, a 3 year old female Mountain Cur mix.  She has a smooth light tan coat with the black muzzle and head like a Cur.  Annabel is a good size dog weighing 40 pounds and this is full grown.  She was pulled from our local animal shelter where she had been picked up by Animal Control as a stray and no one came down to claim her.
 
Annabel can be a little shy and cautious on first meeting but warms up once she gets to know you.  We adopted her out but she was returned after 5 months.  It seems Annabel likes to be in control of the attention she gets and independent in her own space. She’s a little like a cat, she is so sweet and wants attention but will walk away and do her own thing once she’s had enough love! Then, after a break, she usually comes back for more! She was stressed and anxious in her new home and had stomach and incontinence issues, no fault of the adopters, we just think she needed “space and yard time to just be a regular dog.” 

Once she got back to our facility we gave Annabel the largest run and has her own yard to hang out in and she LOVES this!  She has been so happy and not had any stomach or incontinence issues. She has also started playing the most relaxed games of fetch ever! We still bring her in at night and crate her and she has had no issues.  So we feel she would be happy as an outside dog during the day.  She loves seeing people and being loved on so she is not to be just left in the yard with no attention.
 
Annabell recently completed her treatment for heart worm and is on prevention. She is back to her normal loving self and regular activity! 

Annabel is a very sweet, loving dog.  She loves to be with people but just not all the time it appears.  However she doesn’t seem to like young boys, something must have happened in her past cause she does get upset and barks a lot when sees a young male.  We feel she may be better in a home with no children.  She seems to get along with other dogs but would certainly do a trial to make sure.  We all love Annabel – her quirks and all – and she gives lots of love right back to you!

Annabel is up to date with her vet care, spayed and is microchipped.  She is on flea/tick prevention.  Annabel just needs that special home where she feels comfortable and loved but yet still have her independence. 

All HSWA dogs are either at our Dog Adoption Facility or in foster homes. All dogs require an appointment to meet.  Please call us at 205-554-0011 or email humaneswa@yahoo.com to request an appointment to see the dog/puppy and to check availability.

Visit us on Facebook! www.facebook.com/humaneswa

Our adoption fee is $75.  Read more information on our adoption process at www.humanesocietyofwa.org/howtoadopt.html.  Then, if you feel your home might be the right forever home and you would like to adopt a dog, submit an online adoption application. The online applications may not work on mobile devices. If the online application does not work on your device, look to the right side of the forms page for a downloadable .PDF copy of the application.

animal.description:
IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET PLEASE SUBMIT THE ADOPTION APPLICATION VIA OUR WEBSITE: WWW.TAILSOFHOPEDOGRESCUE.COM. THANK YOU! ADOPTION IS $150.00.

You know what we don't want to do? We really don't want to have Augie spend another Christmas with us! Nope, we want him to spend Christmas with a family all his own!
We just don't get t?
This boy is a doll! He needs a shepherd savvy family that wants a big ole lovebug of a dog and is just willing to give him a forever home.
The fact he has been with us since a pup may have folks questioning what " might be wrong with him"? Nothing at al!
Augie came to us as a young pup and by the time he was ready for adoption COVID hit, meaning no events, no exposure. So here we are.
Augie has been neutered, he is microchipped, he tested negative for heartworms, he weighs about 65 pounds, he is crate trained, he does well on car rides, he needs a strong handler for leash walks, he hates squirrels, he is not a fan of cats so no-go on that, and more than anything he needs a family that will be patient and permit him to adapt to a forever home.
Augie is a shepherd so he needs to " work". That means he thrives having activities! Things as simple as keeping a basket of toys in a livingroom and teaching them to " clean up" by gathering toys. This is actually a great activity and sometimes doubles as a searching or hunting game. Taking him for a long walk, a jog, a bike ride, or for play in the park, are all great activities.

Shepherds do best in active homes, so if you have one, make this a priority. Excess energy will lead to misbehavior, dogs are like children in that regard. Give them something to do, something that helps them burn off that energy, and they will be happy.

animal.special_needs_notes: Hans has auto-immune disease which is totally under control with 1/4 a prednisone, every other day. He was pulled from a rescue group in Port Aransas. he was minutes away from euthanasia! Hans was intact, heartworm positive. We decided to take him into our rescue after I saw his face on a rescue plea and noone was stepping up. Something just told me this guy only a year old deserved a second chance to live. I met the rescue to pick up Han's he still had huge ticks all over his body. He had been given tick prevention but there were so many still clinging to him. He was very thin his backbone was sticking up and you could see his ribs. It's taken just over a year to get him healthy. We found out after x-rays were taken he had been shot with a pellet gun many times. His back seemed painful to touch. Our regular vet thought he could have a tick born disease?  After x-rays and several blood panels the vet referred us to a local specialist, Dr. Tyson a internal medicine doctor at the Central Texas Veterinary Specialty hospital in Round Rock. After blood work and steroids it was determined he had autoimmune disease, which is controled with a small amount of prednisone.  Prednisone is very reasonable financially, so really not a burden in that department.  We got the ok for heartworms treatment which was several months of recovery and then he got neutered. Hans has been retested he is heartworm negative.  He does not have back pain anymore and is a happy, healthy boy. He's one of Dr.Tyson's favorite patients.  Han's does not mind the vet at all it's old news to him!

animal.description:
ALL PETS AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION ONLY TO RESIDENTS OF THE DALLAS/FT WORTH METROPLEX

MEET AND GREET APPOINTMENTS SET UP WITH PRE-APPROVED APPLICATION ONLY

We received a message in early 2018 about a momma dog with puppies living under someone’s porch in south TX. Momma was a street dog just looking for a safe place. By the time we were notified the finder couldn’t catch mom and only 5 of the 8 pups were under her porch as she knew a neighbor took 2 which broke our heart. Transport brought us the 5 pups with the hope of Mom and her other pup to follow.  She eventually befriended mom who we named Marie (after her caretaker) and she and her other pup were finally able to make the trip to north TX. Marie was extremely shy as she had spent her life fending for herself on the cruel streets of South TX so living in a house surrounded by people was a very scary thing. 

We were confident that one day Marie would learn to love life as an indoor family pet .... and she proved us right!  She now seeks out attention and love from her foster family so we know with a little patience she is going to thrive in a forever home! Marie is 3-4 years old, approx 45 lbs and way over due having a family to call her own. Marie currently lives with dogs of all sizes and cats.

If you would like to meet Marie, the first step in the process is to complete an application.  Please go to roadtrip4paws.com and click on the Adopt tab to find a link to our online application or copy the following link to your browser  https://form.jotform.com/53098141083150.  

Home visits required for all dog adoptions

We reserve the right to refuse placement of an animal for any reason

animal.description:
Hi my name is Lilo (like from the movie Lilo & Stitch)! I am a year and a half old and around 40 pounds. My fosters believe I am a cur / feist mix due to the shelter I came from and my spunky squirrel lovnig (chasing) personality. I spent 3 months with my training auntie to work on my leash reactivity (which, I'm a teenager, cut me some. slack!) Aunti just LOVED me so much, her favorite thing to say about me is "this dog is so fun!" . 

I need a 6foot privacy fence due to my kangaroo like jumping abilities! I enjoy kongs, puzzle toys, sniffaris, and snuffle mats for mental stimulation.

All I want is a forever home with an active family (or semi active - fun agility at home doggo!) as I make a great sidekick!

I wouldn't mind a brother to play with that is my size or bigger since I just love to play and am too pushy for most other females and those little dogs are so pesky(no offense!).
I require a really good one on one decompression with slowly getting me to play and meet my Stitch. I don't require a brother, and would be happy just doing COVIID-19 at home agility coursse or basic bonding at home.

I AM A BIG cuddler and love waiting for your direction on what's on the list of fun next! I love goofing around and playing with my stuffed toy, tossing it around and chasing after it, as I can keep myself entertained for hours!

I am a very sweet dog when people come to visit and knows no stranger and excited to meet (and get pets) from everyone I comes across. I would need to live with older kids in the home since I am super bouncy and love giving hugs. 

Lilo prefers male dogs, plays loud and rough but will calm down when redirected, and enjoys cuddles and hugs. 
 

Crate trained, house traiend, leash trained - but we'd prefer a calmer non-hiking no dog parking (until her leash reactivity is 100% worked on) lifestyle for her.

Apply here: https://petstablished.com/pets/public/492358

Adoption process: fouron.org/adoption-process

We will not answer questions pertaining to questions that are clearly stated on her profile, already due to the overwhelming amount of inquiries we recieve. Please apply, and we will match you with the appropraite dog. Thank you!

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE: Due to Ben's fear of riding in a car, we are only considering local adoptions for this lovely old boy.

Ben is a sweet, older, loving and calm Shepherd.  Although Ben is almost completely blind he gets around great. He just needs a quiet, stable, loving home where he can spend his retirement days. He enjoys going in and out, so a dog door and fenced yard would be best for him.

Ben needs a home with no stairs, no cats and no children. He might be okay with another old large dog, but being sight impaired, he can be quick to react because he is not sure what is coming at him.  A quiet, calm only dog home is best.

As with all senior dogs, Ben is slow with some arthritis, so short walks and weight maintenance will be essential. He is on thyroid medication daily, but it is a very inexpensive prescription.

Most of our dogs require a fully fenced yard, this does depend on the individual dogs needs and safety requirements.  

Our dogs are fed a nutrient rich dog food named NutriSource.  Our experience is a high quality dog food keeps vet bills down and well-being high.

If you have any questions please email: claudiaatwag@gmail.com

Visit our website to fill out an Adoption Application  http://www.wagsequimwa.com

Adoption donation fee $250.00  (Please understand this adoption donation goes towards helping all the dogs we rescue)

animal.description: Blue prefers to just be called Blue. And not Old Man Blue which is what we sometimes call him to distinguish him from Baby Blue. At a young-at-heart 9 years old, Blue still has a lot of pep in his step and would like it if you save that Old Man business for someone else, thank you very much! Blues favorite pastime is hanging out in the play yard so he can meander about and do lots of sniffin (and maybe a zoomie or two). He says that is SO much better than sitting in a shelter kennel. Blue is clever, too when hes ready for a treat, he will approach you and demonstrate his perfect sit. Then hopefully, you will demonstrate your perfect treat dispensing! Blue has some handling sensitivities. It may sound complicated but ultimately it means that he needs people to go at his pace and respect his boundaries. His volunteer champion Sophie says that he is a smart, sensitive boy and she always looks forward to spending time with her favorite old man. Blues ideal home would be low-traffic and adult-only. It would also be well-stocked with pupperonis and bully sticks! A perfect day for Blue would start with a nice leisurely walk, followed by breakfast and a nap, then another nap, some treats and a walk, dinner, and then a pre-bedtime nap. We think that sounds pretty perfect too, Blue! To contact his foster, email maggie.lakeway@yahoo.com

animal.description:
About 18 months old, Cyrus was found roaming the streets. Animal Control was called because he was "borrowing" things from a lady's yard to play with.
He was taken to the Allendale County Shelter at a time it was completely empty. The only thing he had to play with was his metal bowl. It became an obsession. He would scoot it across his shelter run day and night. If we took him out for a walk, the bowl came with.
A post on the Allendale County Shelter page about Cyrus went viral, and a couple came forward wanting to adopt him. So we got him neutered. The application looked good. We thought he was finally home.
Unfortunately, he was returned the next day. He has been at our Dogport foster center since then. Here, he has been showered with attention and toys. He has discovered real toys, and he no longer finds metal bowls to be that interesting. He also looks forward to his daily walks.
animal.name: Cyrus

Name: Kermit
Breed: Terrier Mix
Age: 6 years old (as of 2020)
Temperament: Friendly
Good with other dogs: No
Good with Cats: unknown, but can test for approved applicant
Good with kids: Only 12+ years old
Heartworm Status: Negative

Kermit sadly was neglected and confined to a small cage, which prevented his legs from developing correctly. In turn, he does not walk like other dogs as his legs are bowed. He is the sweetest boy and deserves a great family.

 He loves bellyrubs above all else. He also really appreciates being put on a leash and walked for as long as his legs will let him...and then more bellyrubs. This is actually his preferred position, hence his crazy happy photos! He would make a great couch potato kind of dog, perfect family dog. He is very good natured and a jovial kind of dog that has no idea he is any kind of different.

Although our rescue dogs share a common bond with one another, no rescue story is the same (even when similar). Vetting costs vary depending on their health conditions. animal.description:
Hi there, I'm Tillie!

I'm an 11-12 year old miniature poodle mix. I am a spayed female that weighs around 22-lbs. I currently live with other dogs and cats and I do fine but I prefer my alone time with my human. Though I do prefer cats over dogs.I am partially potty-trained, I do have some accidents which I am working on. I do have some health concerns that my future family need to tend to, I am visually impaired and my foster mom believes a bit deaf too. Due to this I get startled very easily and I redirect if approached from behind ( blind spots). AT feeding time I must be separated in a crate to eat I do have some old lady lumps but still considered quite pretty by all... Despite my little quirks I am in search of the perfect home which would entail NO KIDS UNDER 14, and would prefer to be an only dog or live with calm adult dogs.

If interested in adopting me visit http://tucsoncoldwetnoses.com/adoptable-pets/ and fill out the application and my foster mom will get back to you within 24 hours. My adoption fee is $190 plus an additional $21 for my county license.
Sent from my iPhone

*Applications to adopt: wwwTucsonColdWetNoses.com Home Visit / ID and Residence Verification is required. Compliance does not imply or guarantee adoption. Approval is the sole discretion of CWN representative(s).

animal.description:
Bobby was seized in an animal cruelty investigation. He had not been around people much at all, so he was very shy when rescued.  However, he is doing so much better now!  He has been in a foster home for several months and his foster mom gave us this update, "Bobby is about as easy going and relaxed as they come. He’s very sweet and gentle. He can still be a little anxious at times but he’s the sweetest dog around. He spends his time snoozing in his crate or on the couch. Once he’s comfortable with you, he’ll be your snuggle buddy. He even tries to sit on my lap at times! He also likes to follow me around. He adores our dog Jangles and gets along wonderfully with another foster dog in our home, too. He may be mellow inside but loves to run around with the other dogs outdoors. When he’s done, he sits by the door to come in. Bobby is housetrained, crate trained and very quiet. And he usually puts himself to bed at night!"  

Bobby will need a tall and sturdy fence at his new home because he can climb a chain link one. He also needs to go to a home with another dog. He will just feel more comfortable with one as a companion. His date of birth is 7/25/2015 and he weighs about 42 pounds.   

You can submit an adoption application for this sweet boy at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Bobby, and because he can climb a chain link fence, a 6 foot privacy fence is required.

animal.description: Hi!This is Amelia! I had a rough start to life! My brother Taz and I were in doggie jail when we were puppies! We were so excited to get out of there and be adopted together! Unfortunately, we were left alone outside most of the time, but that was ok, we had each other! Then a year later when we were bigger, but still kids, we thought we would be big dogs and get out! But OH NO! We ended up in doggie jail again!!! It was MUCH scarier now than as pups! We were overwhelmed with all the noise, dogs crying and PEOPLE! We had never seen people much before and from the sounds of all the crying, they had to be BAD! Then we heard there was not going to be a second chance for us! But then a rescue took us out. There were less people, but just as scary! They fed us and thankfully left us alone, most of the time anyway. Slowly, since they fed us, gave us warm blankets, and talked soft to us, we were less scared but trembled anytime they came around... cause you never know, right? And sure enough, every week they would touch us all over and take us scary places and just traumatize us like crazy! It was horrible.But one day, we were excited to see them and every day after that was easier. Now, although we are still timid about new things, we love the people that take care of us and play and play with the other dogs and cuddle with the humans at night in bed. Soooo.... they say we are ready for our OWN home with our OWN people. We know it will be scary but they say they will find a MUCH better home than the shelter did AND it will be a home that understands and gives us time. And if, by some reason it doesn't work, they will come get us and keep us safe for the rest of our lives! WE DID GET A SECOND AND LAST CHANCE AFTER ALL!About me! I am a young athletic, happy girl who just wants to be loved and feel safe. I think I would be good at protecting my humans too! I prefer male dogs when playing as bully dogs drive me insane. Who do they think they are??? Bullying is just bad! But I could be an only dog too if I got plenty of play time with my human! I just want to love and be loved and safe. Come see me and see how sweet and pretty I am. I will make you proud!Amelia! Please visit me at http://www.rockyspot.org

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Gus (Augusta) and I am a 10-year-old, female, beagle mix. I have cataracts which essentially make me blind but I am sharp and will learn the layout of your home in no time! I also require insulin injections twice a day with my meals but I love food so I usually don’t even notice that I’m getting it. My previous owner told Speak! that he will continue to pay for my insulin following my adoption. I am also a cancer survivor! In February 2020, I had a cancerous liver mass removed. My surgeon says I can expect a cancer-free future and I am feeling better than ever!

I currently weigh about 35 pounds; I am the perfect size. Despite my blindness, I am agile and sweet as can be. I really like to play and take short walks. Napping on a nice, soft bed or couch is another of my favorite pastimes.

My foster sister is a cat and we get along just fine. I am not very fond of other dogs; they tend to startle me and get up in my face which is aggravating when you’re blind like me.  I am completely house trained and I let you know when I need to go out. 

I have a moderate energy level. Most of the time, I simply want to be near you and get some good head scratches. A fenced yard is good for me since I don’t always know where I’m at. I love my harness and walk well on a leash. 

I am a trusting and happy dog and don’t even need to be crated when my foster mom is away. I will be up-to-date on my vaccinations and spayed at the time of my adoption. My adoption fee is $200. Please let us know if you have any questions or believe I would make a great companion for you!

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption policies and apply online at [www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt).

Visit [www.speakfortheunspoken.com](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/) will give you more information about our rescue.

***PLEASE READ*** WE DO NOT RESPOND TO PETFINDER OR EMAIL INQUIRIES. Please fill out an application on our website if you are interested in adopting this dog. We will only set up a meeting with the dog once you have an approved adoption application. We actively manage our dogs on Petfinder, the dogs listed are available for adoption. We will remove the dog from view once they are pending adoption.

If you are interested in adopting Miracle, please go to https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf to print and fill out an application. Since he is currently living in a foster home, please email your completed application to fostering@iheartdogs.org and our foster coordinator will follow-up to discuss next steps!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

***The remaining $150 of Lola's adoption fee has been sponsored.***

Hey everyone, I'm Lola! I'm a shy girl, but I'm a sweetie - that's what my foster mom says. Like a lot of dogs, no one really knows my story before being rescued, so patience will get you far with me. That, and butt scratches. I hear they say "What Lola Wants, Lola Gets," so butt scratches, it is. I really prefer to be the only apple of your eye, and can't live with other dogs or cats now.

I love to go on walks and play in the water, especially the hose! My foster mom says I'm a smart girl who knows sit, lay, and crate on command (although I don't tear stuff up), and I would love to learn more. She says I love to cuddle, but am ok being alone as well, and if I'm feeling especially spunky, I will even show you my zoomies, and they are FUN-ny! Some things I don't like are thunderstorms, fireworks, and car rides.  

I want my own family so bad!! Remember, "What Lola Wants, Lola Gets", so help me get what I want!

**Lola is currently in a WI foster home!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is sponsored.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

I am a 6-7 year old Chihuahua. I am a neutered male and weigh around 12 lbs. I am a sweet boy once I am comfortable with people around me but I do tend to get nervous around new people, mainly men. I am potty trained and crate trained. I do LOVE treats so if you are worried about becoming my friend this is the way to my heart! I do have this nervous-tick and spin in circles and get a little irritated with myself and because of this I would be better to live in a home with no children. I am also a bit sensitive to touch in some areas and can get bitey.. I am a sweet loving boy that has some quirks that need work but I am great with dogs( as long as they are respectful) and don't really mind the cats either!

If you are interested in adopting me and understand that I will need to stay on task from what i have learned in my training. please visit tucsoncoldwetnoses.com/adoptable-pets/ and fill out the application and my foster mom will get back to you within 24 hours. My adoption fee is $175 plus an additional $21 for my county license.

*Applications to adopt: wwwTucsonColdWetNoses.com Home Visit / ID and Residence Verification is required. Compliance does not imply or guarantee adoption. Approval is the sole discretion of CWN representative(s).

animal.description: JOSIE is an approx 3 yr old, smallish Pit bull mix who was found limping around the city of Baltimore. At first it was thought that she had a painful birth defect but once they got in there to amputate it looked more like a bad break that had never been treated. Whether it was foul play or an accident we will never know. Josie has adapted well to tri-pawed life! While she has healed completely on the outside, we are working on her healing from the inside. Someone must have been terribly mean to Josie. She was totally shut down when she arrived As terrified as she has been, Josie has never been snappy. She lets us hook up a leash and take her on walks which is helping her gain some confidence bit by bit. Josie is great with other dogs, not yet tested with cats but she is panicked by people. Looking for a home with another dog and a patient family who can make baby steps with her. Josie has been spayed, vaccinated, tested neg for heartworms and is microchipped. Adoption $200. Super special families apply at www.companimals.org.

animal.description:
Hi Im Ringo Star. Im all male , and as cute as a button. I would love to jump up in your lap , and be your best friend. I'm full of energy too!
My fur is mostly black on top ,and brown on bottom, its kinda long, but the cool thing is I don't shed hardly at all!! I love to run, and greet you,  and give you lots of kisses. I was found traveling with my big brother Rusty Ruff in June .  I am only for adoption with Rusty Ruff, my brother..The nice people here couldnt find my old owners. They took us to the vet to have everything done.... So now  we are waiting for that fantastic , loving home of our very own! My dream would be to have a family adopt me and Rusty Ruff together. We are best friends after all. We were found traveling together, and we are about the same age. See the last pic of us playing in the yard together....I love my dry food, and  esp when they put wet food on top too. I am house broken, and I love my crate. I would very much enjoy trips to training school with you. Id love and do require a big  5-6 ft  height fenced yard to play in, with your dogs, and Rusty Ruff too!.... The vet said I am around  3 years old. I dont bark alot, but when first put in my crate, i will bark just a little.
I do like to do some jumping up, because I get so excited, so small kids prob not a good idea. I weigh about 30 pounds. I am a jumper and will get out of a 6ft fence if there are things for me to jump on, and jump over, so the rescue says I must go to a very special home, that includes both of us   with dog savy people!  
Please contact my people soon, so I and  Rusty Ruff my brother can begin our new exciting life with you.      Thanks  Ringo Star

animal.description:
Sometimes, were all just searching for a happy ending. Sweet Ethan thought he had that twice. First, when this blind and deaf sweet Aussie/border collie puppy was rescued by Speak from an irresponsible breeder and then again when he found his way to a great adopter. But life happens and Ethans people are no longer able to care for him. Full of heartbreak, Ethans dad realized the best thing for this pup is to find a home where he will have an amazing life.

Ethan is one year old, is crate trained and is doing fantastically with touch commands. Hes not a fan of puppies or dogs that are smaller than he is, but does well with bigger pups -- as long as its not dinner time. Hed prefer a home without cats or small children. He will also require a fenced yard. So incredibly sweet, Ethan would excel best in a quiet environment where things are calm, and this joyful boy can have the loving life he deserves.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Ubert! Ubert is an adorable petite Shepherd mix born in 2015 and rescued in Texas. We were able to save Ubert along with several others from a severe warehouse hoarding situation. This poor boy spent so much time suffering through horrendous neglect and now we are so glad that he finally has a chance to have the best new life! Ubert has gotten all the medical care he needed with our vet partner. His eyes were cloudy as a result of tick borne diseases that he acquired that were never treated. All of this has been resolved and as you can see his beautiful eyes are back to normal and as beautiful as ever! Ubert is such a handsome boy and despite what he has endured is very sweet although a bit anxious. Men scare Ubert, so he will need to go slowly with an understanding family if there are males in the home. Ubert doesn't really know what to expect from life, so he needs to progress in baby steps. He is good with other dogs. We can't wait to see Ubert finally enjoying a warm, safe, comfy home of his own where he can get all the unconditional love that he has not known yet. If you can be the special person who can give this special prince his happy ever after, please fill out an adoption application for Ubert here! Www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

He had arrived to them when his family moved out and left him behind. He's social and friendly with people but does not seem to be a fan of other dogs.

Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; SCPR believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.doitforthedogs.com. We are the Second Chance Pet Rescue in Grove, OK. 918-786-7630. You can email us at doitorthepets@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Breed: Pit Bull mix
Sex: Female
DOB: ~09/20/2018
Weight: 49.8 lbs
Good with: Some dogs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Timid but Loyal, Snuggle Bug!
History: Stray
Ideal Home: No cats or kids! Apartments ok if no breed restrictions!
Special Info: Knows some commands, good on leash!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Quinn was rescued from Memphis, TN in July of 2019. He spent some time in a temporary foster home before he traveled up to New York on September 7th to join his permanent foster family. He was Heartworm positive, but has undergone treatment and has recovered well.

Quinn a big strong boy at around 66 lbs and is estimated to be around four years old. He is selective about who he trusts and will need continual training and reinforcement to teach him that new people and strangers are okay. For this reason only homes with experience will be considered. 

With his foster family he is a big lover and just wants to be near his people. He will follow you from room to room to make sure he's not missing anything. He is not a barker and prefers to snuggle at your feet or next to you on the couch. He knows his commands and follows verbal directions well. 

He is a submissive dog and does well with other dogs and kids with proper introductions. No cats for Quinn as he will chase. Because of his size children 6 and up would be best. He would love a family with older kids who could play with him and tire him out!

Because of his Heartworm status he will need to be kept on monthly preventatives for the rest of his life with no exception. He also needs someone with considerable experience, preferably a strong personality who understands dog behavior and training. If you think you are a good match for Quinn, apply at http://bit.ly/HHAdoptApp and we will be in touch!

animal.description:
Good With Kids: Teenagers and up Good With Other Dogs: Poppy is very dog selective Good With Cats: No House trained: Yes Crate Trained: Yes Walks Nicely On A Leash: Yes Knows Basic Commands: Yes - a proud graduate of Training classes Energy Level (Couch Potato, Moderate or High): Moderate Special Needs: N/A Physical Fence: Required Arrival story: We found Poppy at Detroit Animal Care and Control, pregnant. She arrived as a stray. Her ten pups have found their new homes, so now it's Poppy's turn! Approximate Age / Weight: 2..5 years and 63lbs. Personality: Miss Poppy became pregnant when she was really just a pup herself. Our vet believes this could have been her second litter. Luckily, our girl is food-motivated and already walks nicely on a leash. She’s happiest when outside, rolling on the ground and getting awesome belly rubs! Poppy also enjoys noshing on a chew toy. She can be a bit pushy, not realizing her size and manners at times, but has graduated from training class and continues to work on this in her foster home. Poppy is interested in playing with other dogs, but hasn’t learned good manners or appropriate social skills in that department so being an only dog is best. Forever Home: Poppy is very nervous and not confident when meeting new people. She does not trust others quickly and prefers a quiet home or a family that knows to keep Poppy safe when people come over by crating her in another room. She’s a very strong and determined girl, so a physical fence is a must! No invisible and no tie out. Once she trusts her people she is awesome!! She loves to cuddle, loves her walks, and loves playing fetch and tug. Poppy needs experienced dog owners and to be the only dog in the household. Please contact wtdr2008@yahoo.com if interested in adopting Poppy!

Pre-Adoption Application:

To be considered for a dog, it is best to submit a pre-adoption application. The pre-adoption application can be downloaded from our website - www.waggintailsdogrescue.org/adoptionprocess.html. Just complete the application and email it back to wtdr2008@yahoo.com

Waggin' Tails Adoption Information:

Waggin' Tails Dog Rescue has a standard adoption fee of $225 for adult dogs. Different adoption fees apply for older dogs, small breeds and puppies - $125 for senior dogs (9 years +) , $275 for small breed dogs and $250 for puppies, plus a $50 deposit which is returned upon proof of spay/neuter. Our adoption process includes an application, vet reference checks, and a home visit.

Waggin' Tails Dog Rescue does not have a shelter facility. All of our dogs are fostered in private homes. To meet a dog in person, please see our event calendar on our website at www.waggintailsdogrescue.org for the latest information. Arrangements can be made to meet our rescue dogs outside of Saturday adoption events after an approved application is submitted. This application does not imply an obligation to adopt by the applicant or by the rescue group.

Our volunteers have made rescue a second job that they do in their spare time after coming home from full-time jobs. E-mail inquiries are the quickest way to obtain information about a dog.

Thank you for your support of rescue and your interest in a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Trapper lived the first year of her life on the streets by herself. She had never been touched by a human until she came to the shelter.  It was sheer luck that we got her and her 12 babies in the shelter. Her babies have long since been adopted and now we hope to find Trapper a forever home.  She is still weary of humans but hopefully over time she will warm up. She is treat motivated (hot dogs are her favorite) and walks well on a leash. Potential adopters should expect to spend a few days getting to know her before taking her home. Fenced/escape proof yard is a must as she would prefer to be on her own again.  She is sweet, just timid. If you have experience with these hard case dogs, please do not hesitate to contact us and/or come see Trapper.  

Trapper does not like small animals (small dogs or cats), but she does well with calm dogs her size.  

WE ARE CURRENTLY OPERATING BY APPOINTMENT ONLY DUE TO COVID-19
Unless otherwise stated, the adoption fees for dogs over 5 months range from $50-$175. Puppies under 5 months are $175.00. Cats over 1 year are $35.00, kittens under 1 year old are $60.00. Dog adoption fees include a microchip. Cats can be microchipped by request for an additional $5.00.
The adoption fee includes the animal's surgery, vaccinations, flea preventative, deworming medication, sample bag of food/treat samples and a free first exam with participating veterinarians. Shelter policy and 2018 Indiana state law decrees all animals must be spayed or neutered prior to leaving the shelter.
WE ARE CURRENTLY OPERATING BY APPOINTMENT ONLY DUE TO COVID-19
Our shelter is open to the public on Monday- Saturday from 8:00 am -5:00 pm EST with the exception of Wednesdays on which we typically open by 1:00 pm. If you would like to make an appointment to meet one of our many adoptable animals, please send an email to us at pvchs@joink.com. To apply to adopt, you may download an adoption application from the Applications and Fees tab on our website. The web address is www.pvchs.cfsites.org. Please email the completed application to pvchs@joink.com.

animal.description:
Breed: Pit Bull mix
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~12/20/2013
Weight: 56 lbs
Energy Level: Low-Medium
Personality Type: Adaptable and Smart!
Good with: Dogs, no cats please
History: Transferred in from another shelter, adopted and abandoned at
Ideal Home: No cats or kids (teenagers ok!). Low-traffic home. 
Special Info: Knows a TON of commands and always willing to learn more! A bit of a couch potato indoors but enjoys walks, swimming, and playing with other dogs.

If you are interested in adopting Dexter, please go to https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf to print and fill out an application. Since he is currently living in a foster home, please email your completed application to fostering@iheartdogs.org and our foster coordinator will follow-up to discuss next steps!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

11/14/2019: GOLIATH WAS RETURNED. Apparently Goliath does not do well with chickens and was killing the adopter's chickens. Goliath is also a velcro dog and needs a person that will be with him most of the time. He is the biggest sweetheart well, iif you are not a chicken) and just wants to be someone's baby. Goliath, although deaf, does understand facial expressions and hand signals). He actually listens quite well. 10/9/2019: GOLIATH IS NEUTERED AND READY TO GO! HE IS LISTED AS SPECIAL NEEDS BECAUSE THE VET BELIEVES THAT GOLIATH IS DEAF AS HE DOES NOT RESPIND TO SOUNDS/NOISES/OR BEING CALLED. HE HAS ALSO, UNFORTUNATELY, TESTED POSITIVE FOR HEARTWORMS AND ERLICHIOSIS SO HE HAS NOT BEEN WELL CARED FOR IN THE PAST. GOLIATH CAN RECOVER FROM BOTH HEARTWORMS AND ERLICHIOSIS. HE IS BEING STARTED ON A MONTHLY IVERMECTIN TREATMENT FOR THE HEARTWORMS (IVERMECTIN ONCE A MONTH IS ALSO WHAT WE USE TO TREAT HEARTWORM NEGATIVE DOGS SO NO "SPECIAL" CARE IS REQUIRED) AND HE IS ON DOXYCYCLINE FOR THE ERLICHIOSIS (A TICK BOURNE DISEASE). GOLIATH IS A GOOD BOY AND WILL MAKE A GREAT PET BUT BECAUSE HE IS DEAF, HE WILL NEED A HOME WHERE HE IS NOT ABLE TO ROAM OR WHERE HE WOULD BE STARTLED (IE BEING GRABBED FROM BEHIND) BECAUSE HE CANT HEAR, HIS BEW OWNER WILL NEED TO BE MINDFUL ABOUT MAKING THEIR PRESENCE KNOWN TO HIM. GOLIATH WALKS WELL ON A LEASH AND HAS THE CUTEST GRIN. WHAT HE HAS LOST ON HIS HEARING, HE HAS GAINED IN HIS OTHER SENSES
Goliath is a large great pyrenees mix. He is white in color with a couple of brown patches on his back. Goliath was found on a womans property. We have attempted to locate Goliaths owners with no success so he will be looking for a new forever home. Great pyrenees, by nature, enjoy patrolling and roaming their property, and territory (as they see it...even if that means it extends beyond their property line).They are guardian dogs and enjoy having a job. Goliath would do great on a farm guarding livestock or he would probably also enjoy being a family pet as well. Just remember that he may want to herd your children or other pets. He is a very large boy so he could knock little ones over, although pyrenees are generally known to be gentle giants, unless you are a predator threatening their flock. Because pyrenees are known to roam, a secure fenced yard or regular leash walking is necessary to prevent him from wandering off and finding himself homeless once again, although he will be chipped which would, hopefully, help him find his way back home. He is a boisterous dog who loves to rough-house with dominate female dogs and lets them beat him up. When people play with him, he is best directed by treats. *****Special note about his video*****Bucky is a sweet playful dog, but has anxiety about meeting new people. We believe that the best thing for Bucky is for a potential adopter to visit him at the shelter several times before trying to do an official meet and greet for adoption. We can set you up to observe him with others he already knows. Spending time with him on walks at the shelter and giving him treats will be the best way to his heart. This will take a little extra time and effort on your part but it could be worth it for you. We have done this slow-meet technique with another one of our dogs who didn't make a good first impression and it paid off for the family who adopted him! They are very grateful to have him in their family now.Please fill out an application to meet him!

animal.description:
Meet Stitch
Courtesy Post

I was a feral dog my whole life. When I wandered up to the shelter on a cold Feb evening, little did I know I’d spend the next 1,000 days there. I haven’t been well since birth, legs are bowed most likely due to growth plate injuries when I was little. Stitch has struggled with weight all his life. 2yrs of trails, experimenting with medication, exploratory surgery & vets determined I had a malabsorption disorder & would never put on weight. After 2yrs at the shelter through all weather & no interest. I was finally adopted. However it was short lived when my owner lost his home & couldn’t care for me. I ended up in foster care, so no more shelter for me. But still, something wasn’t right. I was lethargic, depressed & had no interest in eating. My rescue family was determined to figure it out. 2wks at the vet, hundreds later & so many blood tests. Finally determined I had Tick-borne disease called Babesia. Babesia is a very serious blood disease that can have deadly side effects if left undiagnosed & untreated. It is extremely hard to test positive  for & requires a lot of testing by the vets. We don’t know how I got it but thankfully I received my treatment & am on the up side of this fight! The Dr said I’D ACTUALLY look like a normal dog 1 day. Which I haven’t ever! I’m eating, playing  & still patiently waiting for my forever family. A family that understands the misunderstood, out of the ordinary, spunky & unconditional love. I am about 4yrs old, current on shots, neutered, microchipped & house/crate trained. I’m good with kids & other dogs!!! I love car rides, walks, outings & pretty much anything you want to cook for me! Oh I am a bed hog, couch potato & tennis ball loving man! Please consider opening your heart & home to Stitch 

If you are interested in adopting, please go to www.thepitstoprescue.com

animal.description:
Meet Allie
Courtesy Post

Over 2yrs ago, our Allie was rescued. We wish we could say that was the end of her hard life, but it was just the begining. She was found in an abandoned trailer park which flooded. We are unsure if she was left, wandered or was dropped off there. It was not a safe area, so there is no telling. She was living under one of the trailers & her only friends were the stray cats. The rescue that found her reached out to us for help. We knew this baby has been through a lot & was very confused! From the start Allie has had complicating allergies & has had it rough. No she couldn’t go out to play with other dogs, sleep/rest or eat without itching. She itched until she bled, had daily baths, had to wear pjs & through the course of all of this the Drs struggled to pinpoint the root of her allergies. She was tested multiple times, placed on so many different oral & skin medications, that we lost count. Thousands of dollars later & to many days to count, she is slowly making progress. We refuse to give up on Allie. Even though she has her bad days, she doesn’t let that get her down! She is the perfect balance of playful & calm, She loves to be silly & play around but also loves to nap! She is now about 2yrs old, spayed, current on shots, on heart worm prevention, microchipped. Allie is good with other dogs, kid & cats. Please consider opening your heart & home to Allie. 

If you are interested in adopting, please go to www.thepitstoprescue.com

animal.description:
Eleven
1 year old. Female. Mastiff mix. 70 lbs. Dogs.

Eleven is extraordinary. She is very shy to new people but when she opens up, she lights your heart up like a Christmas tree. A baby yet, she came from CACC. Someone most certainly didn’t treat her the way one should treat a growing baby. But forward we go, and a new love and respected life we learn. She enjoys walks and loves other dogs. We would like to see her in a home with another dog as they make her feel more comfortable and seeing her happy is everything. Super snuggly and sweet once you earn her trust. Of course she thinks she’s a lap dog. She a magical cross of who knows what. Sometimes we see deer in her, other times a Dane or a sorceress dweller from the enchanted forest.

Animals can be viewed by appointment only. We ask that you review our adoption information AND fill out an adoption application prior to setting an appointment so we have all your information and you understand our adoption procedures - you can do so online here.     

Please feel free to email us or call us anytime for additional information on any of our animals - info@mcprescue.org or 312-388-3928. Our typical adoption fee varies based on the age of the dog at the time of rescue: Under the age of 1 years old is $500; 1-5 years old is $400; over the age of 5 is $300. Fees include vaccinations, microchip, deworming and other vetting as needed. Our adoption process includes an application, reference check and home visit.
